Service Usage

A Party is any person or organisation that directly or indirectly interacts with any of DIACs core businesses. A Party can be recorded and allocated a unique Party Identifier in any number of DIAC systems that manage this interaction.
models.readme:
Service Usage

A Party is any person or organisation that directly or indirectly interacts with any of DIACs core businesses. A Party can be recorded and allocated a unique Party Identifier in any number of DIAC systems that manage this interaction.
This service will allow for all known Consolidated (i.e. stored in the CDH) Party Identifiers to be retrieved using any other Party Identifier which is known to the consumer.
This service will be based on the principles of SV176 Transform Identifier but is not dependent on transforming to or from a Party Id (which is the identifier pertaining to the Client Data Hub).
Party or System of Entry (SOE) Identifiers such as ICSE Client Identifier (CID) are specific to provider systems such as ICSE. In order to have the ability to use this specific identifier to retrieve other Party Identifiers, the service requires the actual identifier and its type to be used as input. For example, if the value of the identifier type is CID then the Party Identifier represents the Client Identifier which is used in ICSE.

Service Behaviour

This service retrieves all known Consolidated Party Identifiers (stored in CDH) using any other Party Identifier (stored in CDH) supplied by consumer.
To invoke the service a consumer provides following parameters
Party Identifier
Identifier Type
Status - Status value act as a filter and may have one of ACTIVE, INACTIVE and ALL values. If not provided the service defaults to ACTIVE value.
The response returned has following structure and group of fields
PartyIdentifier
IdentifierType
EndDate

Service Composition

Service Flow

An event is generated by the Service Consumer which invokes the Retrieve Consolidated Party Identifiers service on the ESB;
ESB transforms the incoming request message Retrieve Consolidated Party Identifiers Request to TCRMService as per DIMA_DCD d15 Service Specification - SV288-v01.0 Retrieve Consolidated Party Identifiers.xls and send the message to CDH
CDH executes the Retrieve Consolidated Party Identifiers Request and returns an XML message TCRMService to ESB.
ESB receives TCRMService message and transforms it to Retrieve Consolidated Party Identifiers Response
Alternate Flow 1 (AF1)
The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the CDH provider returns an error.
ESB transforms Error into Enterprise Error Message as per section 4 Return Codes and Messages.
ESB returns response with Enterprise Error payload.
Alternate Flow 2 (AF2)
If the service call was timeout, ESB should return error as per 4 Return Codes and Messages.
to the consumer.

Service State Management Decisions

No state management required

models.description:
Service Usage

This service is to be used to retrieve client notes from the Client Data Hub (CDH) based on optional filtering criteria.
models.readme:
Service Usage

This service is to be used to retrieve client notes from the Client Data Hub (CDH) based on optional filtering criteria.

Service Behaviour

This service returns a list of notes associated with the client. The types of notes retrieved are:
CSP Client Notes (CSP this will not be used until CR03)
Client Additional Info Notes (CAI)
Client of Interest Notes (COI)
Client Contact Details Notes (CCD)
The client contact details notes message will also show its usage code. A party or role identifier must be sent down.
The filters supported are;
Source system
Electronic file reference (TRIM)
Start and End dates
Offset start in the result set and number of records (offset count) to return.
The return list will include the number of notes found, how many notes have been returned and their offset. The implicit order is the Effective From Date of the note.

Service Composition

This service is a single service that calls CDH only. A valid invocation of this service requires either a party or role identifier.

Service Flow

An event is generated by the Service Consumer which invokes the Retrieve Party Note List service on the ESB;
ESB invokes the provider CDH as follows:
ESB will transform RetrievePartyNoteListRequest.xml to CDH. MyTCRM as per data mappings in SV314v01.00Micro.doc
ESB invokes the CDH.MyTCRM service on the CDH
CDH returns CDH.TcrmResponse to the ESB. This will contain all the notes CDH has for this client.
ESB transforms CDH.TcrmResponse to RetrievePartyNoteListResponse.xml
If the client exists, but no notes exist then this service will simply return the result set information showing the result set potential size of zero. Otherwise all the clients notes will be returned. The result set counters are for all notes, regardless of type.
If the party does not exist then a warning will be returned. Other errors will be sent back to the user as per Alternate Flow 1 below.
Alternate Flow 1 (AF1)
The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the primary provider raises an error.
ESB transforms CDH Errors into Enterprise Errors.
ESB returns response with Enterprise Error payload.
See Section 4 on errors returned.
Alternate Flow 2 (AF2)
If the service call was timeout, ESB should return a message to the consumer. See Section 4 on errors returned.

Service State Management Decisions

No state management required

models.description:
Service Usage

This service is used to Notify Client MAL Update's

Service Usage

This service provides a method of maintaining consolidated client information in CDH. Other systems, such as Siebel and GVP, send SV317 notification messages to CDH.
models.readme:
Service Usage

This service provides a method of maintaining consolidated client information in CDH. Other systems, such as Siebel and GVP, send SV317 notification messages to CDH.

The service updates client information. In SfP9 this includes:
Client identifiers
Personal biographic data
Other client information that will be returned in later releases are:
Organisational data (e.g. industry type)
Visa and detention information
Flags, including In Detention, Migration Review Tribunal (MRT) in progress, etc.
Contact information, such as postal address, email address, etc.
Travel documents
At least one of these areas of information must be present and, possibly, more than one can be present. The behaviour of the service depends on which data exist and is described below.

Service Behaviour

The service updates information in the CDH. There must be at least one System of Entry (SoE) identifier. The rules are:
The System of Entry (SoE) identifiers are present to assist CDH to determine if this is a new client or an update to an existing client;
The service returns all SoE identifiers for a client in the response;
If message has only SoE identifiers then it must have at least two and may have more;
If the message has client information then it must have at least one SoE identifier, although it can have more than one SoE identifier; and
If the message has client information and more than one SoE identifier then it updatex the client data and associatex the SoE identifiers.
A consumer invokes the service by providing the System of Entry identifiers (mandatory) and information. For SfP9 this service provides two business functions:
Associate party identifiers; and/or
Update a persons biodata or organisation details.
These functions can be used in the one invocation if multiple SoE identifiers are sent with biodata
Supported Functions
Associate Party Identifiers
As of SfP9, the only party identifiers that can be associated are:
CDHPARTYID
Siebel SCID
Update a Persons Biodata
This function will allow
Person Biographic Data
If the party is unknown to CDH then at least one SoE identifier needs to be provided and the family name or organisation name. The rules for this service are specified later in the service composition section.
The PartyType enumeration must be used to indicate if the party is a PERSON or an ORGANISATION.
Organisation Details
No organisational information is allowed at this time
Information not supported in SfP 9
The following is not supported in this release of SV317:
Person Status (e.g. lawful, unlawful)
Business dealing information (Visa & Detention)
Contact details (e.g. Postal address, email, fax)
Travel Documents
The following flags:
Unaccompanied Humanitarian Minor
In Detention
Active Administrative Appeals Tribunal (AAT) Review
Migration Review Tribunal (MRT) in progress
Refugee Review Tribunal (RRT) in progress
Judicial Review in progress
Ministerial Intervention in progress
Response
The service responds by either:
Acknowledging that the update was successful and returning all the identifiers for the client; or
Indicating that the update was not successful (due to a processing error and/or system timeout).

Service Composition

This service is a single service that calls CDH only. A valid invocation of this service requires either a party or role identifier.

Service Flow

An event is generated by the Service Consumer which invokes the Notify Client Update service on the ESB;
ESB invokes the provider CDH as follows:
ESB will transform NotifyClientUpdateRequest.xml to CDH. MyTCRM as per data mappings in SV317v01.00Macro.doc
ESB invokes the CDH. MyTCRM service on the CDH. CDH will:
IF the client is unknown to CDH then the client will create the client;
IF the client is known then CDH will amend the client;
IF only SoE identifiers are sent and the client is known then CDH will update the SoE identifiers with its internal client identifier if it can match the client.
CDH returns CDH. TcrmResponse to the ESB. This will contain all the client identifiers CDH have for this client.
ESB transforms CDH. TcrmResponse to NotifyClientUpdateResponse.xml
Service Flow
There are a number of conditions that need to be handled. These are:
IF CDH receives a list of one or more identifiers, none of which can be matched to an existing client, and sufficient client details for the client to be created then a client is created;
IF CDH receives a list of one or more identifiers, none of which can be matched to an existing client, and no further details then CDH will return an error;
IF CDH receives a list of one or more identifiers, of which one or more can be associated with a single client, then CDHs internal association of SoE identifiers to its CDH party identifier should be updated;
IF CDH receives a list of one or more identifiers, of which one or more can be associated with a single client, and client data then CDHs internal association of SoE identifiers to its CDH party identifier should be updated and the clients data should be updated; and
IF CDH receives a list of two or more identifiers that identify two separate clients an error is raised.
Alternate Flow 1 (AF1)
The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the primary provider raises an error.
ESB transforms CDH Error into Enterprise Error Message.
ESB returns response with Enterprise Error payload.
Alternate Flow 2 (AF2)
If the service call was timeout, ESB should return SV317.MSG-E02 to the consumer.

models.description:
Service Usage

SV341 Retrieve Identified Consolidated Party provides the ability to search and retrieve consolidated summary of an identified party. The options to identify and retrieve consolidated party summary are as under:
models.readme:
Service Usage

SV341 Retrieve Identified Consolidated Party provides the ability to search and retrieve consolidated summary of an identified party. The options to identify and retrieve consolidated party summary are as under:
To retrieve an already identified party by providing its party identifier or.
To retrieve a party by providing search criteria such as Visa Evidence number and Date of Birth, or a Transaction Reference Number TRN.
This service performs exact party identification based on the supplied criteria, for details see section 1.4 Service Behaviour, and does not perform fuzzy name search on the given bio-graphic details. This service will be used by Generic Visa Portal to perform a client match and retrieve all relevant data to perform an assessment.
If a single party is successfully identified, the service response includes list of party identifiers and summary attributes as per section 1.9.2 Service Response Message.
If multiple parties are identified, the service response will retrieve list of party identifiers and summary attributes as per section 1.9.2 Service Response Message. Identified Multiple parties retrieved in response will be limited to 10.
If no party is identified, the service will respond with no match found message.

A Party is any person or organisation that directly or indirectly interacts with DIACs core business. A Partys interaction with DIAC is defined by one or many different Roles e.g. a Person can have the role of Applicant, Sponsor or Agent. An Organisation can have roles including Agency and Sponsor.
By design, Party information will be consolidated in the Client Data Hub (CDH) to support the 360 degree view of Party; the SV341 service will allow consumers to search and retrieve the consolidated summary information, along with a summary of business dealings information.

Service Behaviour

Service will retrieve an identified party on the basis of the supplied party identifiers. In case the party is not already identified, the party identification is done on the following basis.
Person identification and retrieval:
Client identification, excluding contact recipient; Migration Agent and Authorised recipient, is based on the following criteria and order.
Party Identifier
visa evidence number and Date of Birth
Transaction Reference number and Date of Birth (compare DOB provided with primary applicant on TRN)
Passport number, country of passport, and Date of Birth
Person Biodata Details:
Family Name
Given Name
DOB
Birth Country code
Sex code
If using a higher level search criteria party is not found then the next level criteria is used to identify party along with an appropriate warning message.
For a Person Search, this service doesnt match on contact recipient, Migration Agent and Authorised recipient.
Organisation identification and retrieval
Organisation identification is based on following criteria and order:
Party Identifier
Transaction Reference Number
Organisation identifier:
Organisation Registered Name (Current)

Service Variants

SV324 RetrieveConsolidatedPartyNameSummary, SV288 Retrieve Consolidated Party Identifiers, SV368 Retrieve Consolidated Party Addresses

Service Dependencies

None.

Service Composition

This service is not a composite service i.e. it is not composed of other services within the Service Portfolio.

Service Flow

An event is generated by the Service Consumer or a System which invokes the Retrieve Identified Consolidated Party service on ESB;
ESB will transform Retrieve Identified Consolidated Party request to CDH request format as per the mappings specified in the associated micro document.
CDH will send response message to ESB.
ESB will transform the CDH response message to Retrieve Identified Consolidated Party response message as per the mappings specified in the associated micro document.
ESB will return the response message to the Service Consumer.
Alternate Flow 1 (AF1)
The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the primary provider raises an error.
Primary provider CDH returns a specific error code to the ESB; see section Error! Reference source not found. Error! Reference source not found. of this document for a full listing of Return Codes and Messages.
ESB transforms error code into Enterprise Error Message.
ESB returns response with Enterprise Error payload to the consumer.
Alternate Flow 2 (AF2)
If the ESB raises an error before or while attempting to contact the primary provider, it will respond to the consumer with the relevant Enterprise Error payload. See section 4 of this document for a full listing of Return Codes and Messages.
Alternate Flow 3 (AF3)
If the service call was timeout, ESB should return SV341.MSG-E00 to the consumer.

Transformation

Service State Management Decisions

No State Management required

models.description:
Service Usage

This service will be used by GVP in order to send updates to CDH. The service allows updates for the following business categories:
models.readme:
Service Usage

This service will be used by GVP in order to send updates to CDH. The service allows updates for the following business categories:
Visa applications
Visa cancellations
Sponsorships Applications
Sponsorship Agreements
Nominations Applications

Service Behaviour

A request is sent from the consumer to DI. DI translates this and loads into CDH to update or insert a business dealings. CDH process the message. This service is asynchronous and has no response.

One aspect of this services behaviour concerns when GVP creates a permission request in ICSE to represent its own business dealing. It will use the AssociatedBusinessDealingMsg to inform CDH that ICSE now contains a minimal, or skeleton, permission request that represents the GVP business dealing. The association is ICSE skeleton and CDH will create two references, one for GVP and one for ICSE, to the one business dealing.

This mechanism will ensure that - as long as the business dealing is active, or mastered, by GVP - any ICSE updates to this business dealing will be ignored. Once the business dealing is no longer mastered by GVP; that is, its state becomes inactive, then ICSE updates to the business dealing may be applied by CDH.

The SV278 service will return this association.

When adding or updating a lower level entity, such as a role or contact method, the parent entities must be sent in their entirety, but unaffected sibling entities do not need to be sent. For example, to add or update a related party role the complete Business Dealing Message is required along with the new role, but no sibling roles are required. Likewise, to add a contact method, the business dealing message and the parent role of the contact method need to be a complete snapshot, but sibling contact methods of that role do not need to be sent; likewise unaffected sibling roles of the role sent down do not need to be sent.

Updated the Party Response Message to ensure that we can capture the VLN in context to the business dealing and the interested Party.

Service Variants

None

Service Dependencies

This service is dependent on Datastage

Service Composition

This service uses Datastage as the provider for incoming messages. A valid invocation of this service requires only one business dealing with a valid business dealing id, business dealing category and business dealing source.
The translation of the additional agreement details are as follows:
Business Dealing Id = Agreement number
Business Dealing Type = Agreement Type
Lodgement Date = Agreement Start Date
Expiry Date = Agreement Expiry Date
Any related business dealings have to be sent down as distinct messages. It is in the subsequent related business dealings that the associated business dealing message element is used to show the relationship.
IF a party role is created then at least one of either (both are allowed) party identifier must exist OR an party role identifier may exist.
The required information is:
Associated Business Dealing Id = the other business dealing id in the message
Associated Business Dealing Source = e.g. GVP
Dealing Category = e.g. NOMINATION
Business Dealing Relationship = this attribute requires a value
Note:

  1. The absence of contactPerson in contactMethod implies the actual applicant
  2. Expiry Date = Approval Expiry Date
  3. Application Type was left over from modelling of Sponsorships and Nominations, which are now modelled as separate constructs thereby making this attribute redundant.
  4. If the business dealing relationship is ICSE skeleton then CDH will create a second reference to the GVP business dealing. As long as the GVP business dealing is in an active state then subsequent updates from ICSE to that business dealing will be ignored. Once the business dealing state becomes inactive, then updates from either ICSE or GVP may be applied to the business dealing.

Service Flow

  1. Datastage receives a file in XML compliant with the schema.
  2. Depending on internal rules, either a new business dealing is created or an existing business dealing is update.

Transformation

CDH Internal transformations.

Service State Management Decisions

If an error is discovered then this will need to be addressed by BAU.

models.readme:
Service Usage

SV368 Retrieve Consolidated Party Addresses service provides the functionality to retrieve party addresses for the provided party system identifier.
A Party is any person or organisation that directly or indirectly interacts with DIACs core business. A Partys interaction with DIAC is defined by one or many different Roles e.g. a Person can have the role of Applicant, Sponsor or Agent. An Organisation can have roles including Agency and Sponsor.
By design, Party information will be consolidated in the Client Data Hub (CDH) to support the 360 degree view of Party.
In SFP10 this services functionality was provided by SV277 (now SV325).

Service Behaviour

The SV368 service will allow consumers to retrieve the consolidated addresses information for the following contact method types:
Address
Email
Fax
Telephone
SV368 Retrieve Consolidated Party Addresses interface allows consumers to limit addresses to be retrieved by supplying the following set of optional criteria:
Maximum Retrieve Count
Address Start and End date
Active Address indicator
Contact methods types (Email or Fax etc.)

Service Variants

None

Service Dependencies

None

Service Composition

This service is not a composite service i.e. it is not composed of other services within the Service Portfolio.

Service Flow

  1. An event is generated by the Service Consumer or a System which invokes the Retrieve Consolidated Party Addresses service on ESB;
  2. ESB invokes the primary provider CDH (Client Data Hub) as follows:
    a. ESB will transform Retrieve Consolidated Party Addresses.xml to CDH.retrievePartyRequestObject as per data mappings in the SV368 Retrieve Consolidated Party Addresses micro design spreadsheet.
    b. ESB invokes the CDH.retrievePartyRequestObject service on the CDH
    c. CDH executes the CDH.retrievePartyRequestObject service and returns CDH.retrievePartyResponseObject to the ESB. If the Party does not exist in the CDH then stop flow and return message to consumer (SV325.MSG-E10).
    d. ESB transforms CDH.retrievePartyResponseObject into Retrieve Consolidated Party Addresses.xml as per data mappings in micro design spreadsheet.
  3. ESB returns Retrieve Consolidated Party AddressesResponse.xml to the consumer.
    1.1.1 Alternate Flow 1 (AF1)
    The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the primary provider raises an error.
  4. Primary provider CDH returns a specific error code to the ESB; see section 4 of this document for a full listing of Return Codes and Messages.
  5. ESB transforms error code into Enterprise Error Message.
  6. ESB returns response with Enterprise Error payload to the consumer.
    1.1.2 Alternate Flow 2 (AF2)
    If the ESB raises an error before or while attempting to contact the primary provider, it will respond to the consumer with the relevant Enterprise Error payload. See section 4 of this document for a full listing of Return Codes and Messages.

Service State Management Decisions

No state management required.

Service Behaviour

This service inserts or updates CSP notes in the CDH database. The service requires the following items to insert a new note:

Source system
Party type (organisation or person)
Note text
Note type
Start date
Record timestamp
Create user id

Last actioned by
It will return a note identifier. This can be used to update a note. An update requires the following fields:
Party or role identifier
Source system
Party type (organisation or person)
Note id
End date

Service Variants

Service Composition

ESB invokes the provider CDH as follows:

ESB invokes the CDH.MyTCRM service on the CDH
CDH returns CDH.TcrmResponse to the ESB.
ESB transforms CDH.TcrmResponse to NotifyClientUpdateResponse.xml
This service is either a creation of a new note or the updating of an existing note. If an existing note is updated the only field which can be updated is the EndDate. In either invocation the normal response of this service will be to return a note identifier number. If the note cannot be inserted or if the note id for an update does not exist then the response of the service will be as per Alternate Flow 1 below.

Service Usage

models.readme:
Service Usage

This service will be used by CSP to interrogate the WCC database to obtain a list of clients who have had business or other dealings with the related client.

Service Behaviour

A consumer calls this service with either a party identifier or a party role identifier. If the party does not exist then a warning is returned to the consumer. If the party exists then the list of related parties is returned, along with their various relationships to the main party. The types of relationships that could be returned are:
Parties are related by business dealing
Parties are related by transport (on the same aeroplane)
Parties are related in a familial manner
For SfP11/12, the related parties returned will be for business dealings only. The list of business dealings are:
CITIZENSHIP
VISAAPPLICATION VISACANCELLATION
SPONSORSHIP
AGREEMENT
NOMINATION
AOS
HEALTH_ASSESSMENT
MONITORING
OTHER
VISA

Service Variants

Service Dependencies

None.

Service Composition

This is a single service call to CDH only.

Service Flow

An event is generated by the Service Consumer which invokes the Retrieve Related Party List service on the ESB;
ESB invokes the provider CDH as follows:
ESB will transform RetrieveRelatedPartyListRequest.xml to CDH. MyTCRM as per data mappings in SV402v01.00Micro.doc
ESB invokes the CDH.MyTCRM service on the CDH
CDH returns CDH.TcrmResponse to the ESB.
ESB transforms CDH.TcrmResponse to RetrieveRelatedPartyListResponse.xml
This service returns related parties to the party of interest that are connected, at this stage, through business dealings. If an error in execution or in the service occurs then the response of the service will be as per Alternate Flow 1 below
The service will also return two counts:

models.description:
Service Usage

Consumer of the service will supply the unique VLN in the request and the service provider will provide the matched, finalised or in process of being finalised, details of the biometric identity data held in the system. The response will include a flag to indicate whether the response contains finalised or in process data.
models.readme:
Service Usage

Consumer of the service will supply the unique VLN in the request and the service provider will provide the matched, finalised or in process of being finalised, details of the biometric identity data held in the system. The response will include a flag to indicate whether the response contains finalised or in process data.
This service will potentially become part of the interactions between BAMS and SRS that are required as part of UKVAC Pilot project. As an overall process of UKVAC system this service interface is used by SRS to retrieve biometric data and match results from BAMS, and it is referred as UC-VAC-0.24.

Service Behaviour

The service provider exposes an interface for retrieving details of a biometric identity response details. This service responds with Enterprise Messaging Model (EMM) error codes in any exception scenarios. The request and response messages are sent in EMM format using xml. The current interface is exposed using HTTP transport protocol.

Service Variants

Service Dependencies

None.

Service Composition

SRS initiates this service call when it has established that there are biometrics related to the offshore visa application due to the presence of a VLN and consequently issues a service call to poll BAMS for biometric data. SRS polls BAMS till it receives a final response having ProcessingFinalisedFlag with the true value, or an exception response.

Service Flow

The interaction below is describes an interaction between a consumer system (CS) and BAMS.
Normal Flow
CS initiates the process for retrieving, finalised or in process of being finalised, details of biometric identity data passed to BAMS for matching and assessment as a result of some specific event.
CS invokes BAMS Service SV403 by sending an HTTP request.
BAMS searches within its system for any current jobs or completed jobs based on the VLN supplied.
BAMS sends the response for the one and only one Job found for the supplied match criteria.
CS receives finalised or in-process details on match decisions.
Alternate Flow Duplicate VLN Error
CS initiates the process for retrieving, finalised or in process of being finalised, details of biometric identity data passed to BAMS for matching and assessment as a result of some specific event.
CS invokes BAMS Service SV403 by sending an HTTP request.
BAMS searches within its system for any current jobs or completed jobs based on the VLN supplied.
BAMS finds more than one Job found for the supplied match criteria.
BAMS sends Duplicate VLN Error in Response.
CS receives exception response with PRTY00092 code.
Alternate Flow Data could not be found for the specified request
CS initiates the process for retrieving, finalised or in process of being finalised, details of biometric identity data passed to BAMS for matching and assessment as a result of some specific event.
CS invokes BAMS Service SV403 by sending an HTTP request.
BAMS searches within its system for any current jobs or completed jobs based on the VLN supplied.
BAMS finds no Job for the supplied match criteria.
BAMS sends Job Not Found Error in Response.
CS receives exception response with ENTR00016 code.

Transformation

Service State Management Decisions

State management between multiple calls using the same VLN is implementation dependent and will be based on BAMS internal rules.

models.description:
Service Usage

The service will be used to return a summary of data, for an identified business dealing. This service provides a consolidated summary of a specified business dealing, its related parties and their outcomes in association to that business dealing.
models.readme:
Service Usage

The service will be used to return a summary of data, for an identified business dealing. This service provides a consolidated summary of a specified business dealing, its related parties and their outcomes in association to that business dealing.

Service Behaviour

A request is sent from the consumer to the ESB. The ESB translates this to the CDH API requesting a summary for an identified business dealing and its related parties. The CDH API for the business dealing returns all the information and there should be no orchestration of calls to another provider.
The request will contain a Party Role Identifier to identify the party concerned.
CDM Code CDM Description
ALL All business dealings
CITIZENSHIP Citizenship
VISAAPPLICATION Visa Application SPONSORSHIP Sponsorship NOMINATION Nomination AOS AOS HEALTHASSESSMENT Health Assessment
ADDRESS Address
MONITORING Monitoring
OTHER Other (not currently used)
VISACANCELLATION Visa Cancellation AGREEMENT Agreement ENFORCEMENT Enforcement VISAENTITLEMENTVERIFICATION Visa Entitlement Verification VISA Visa BORDERREFERRAL Border Referral
CLIENTCASE CCMDS Client Case SECURITYREFERRAL Security Referral
CCMDSAPPOINTMENT CCMDS Appointment CCMDSJOB CCMDS Job
CITIZENSHIPAPPOINTMENT Citizenship Appointment HEALTHCASE Health Case
When CDH returns the business summary through the API, ESB will translate this into the service response format and return it to the consumer. A party, with respect to this service, may be either a person or an organisation. This service will return all roles associated with the business dealing.
The service returns a summary for the identified business dealing, it will then return all the related parties associated to that business dealing and the outcomes associated to that party through that business dealing.
A flag may be sent to indicate no related party information is to be sent, no related outcomes to be sent or no related associated business dealings are to be sent.

Service Variants

None

Service Dependencies

This service is dependent on CDH having an appropriate API, or set of APIs, that return the business summary given a party id and, optionally, a business category.

Service Composition

This service is a single service. It will call CDH only. Service Flow
An event is generated by the Service Consumer which invokes the RetrieveConsolidatedPartyBusinessSummary service on the ESB;
This is transformed to the CDH service myTCRM.TCRMInquiry using the InquiryType of RetrieveBusinessDealingSummary. This has the following parameter structure (from the WCC Service Micro Design document see related documents):
Alternate Flow 1 (AF1)
The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the primary provider raises an error.
ESB transforms errors into Enterprise Error Message.
ESB returns response with Enterprise Error payload.
Alternate Flow 2 (AF2)
If the service call was timeout, ESB should return SV416 ENTR00007 to the consumer.
Alternate Flow 3 (AF3)
If no business dealing is found. Return a warning message and a valid response with a no business dealing response flag.

Service Flow

Transformation

Service State Management Decisions

No state management.

models.description:
Service Usage

This service will be used by Health in order to send updates to CDH. The service allows updates for the following business categories:
models.readme:
Service Usage

This service will be used by Health in order to send updates to CDH. The service allows updates for the following business categories:

  • Create Health Case
  • Update Health Case
  • Update Client Contacts
    Health will also send through any associations to existing ICSE HAPR and Visa Application.

Service Behaviour

A message is sent to CDH

As part of the service behaviour any updates that are sent through to CDH must be done so as a whole object. If one element is modified within an object regardless of whether the remaining elements are updated/modified the entire object and its associated elements and the related objects must be sent through, in order to recreate the message in the event that the original create failed.

Service Variants

None

Service Dependencies

In order for SV422 to update the CDH with any creation or updates it is dependant on SV317 association a HAP Applicant ID to the party held in the CDH.

Service Flow

  1. An event is generated by the Service Consumer which invokes the Notify Health Business Dealing Update Request service on the ESB;
  2. Datastage receives a file in XML complaint with the schema.
  3. Datastage will then transform the message into valid XML for WCC.
  4. WCC with then apply any applicable rules, either a new business dealing is created or an existing business dealing is updated.
  5. WCC should always be able to recreate any subsequent updates in the event that the create message may have failed.

Transformation

Please see micro documentation

Service State Management Decisions

No state management required

Service Usage

The service provides the ability to notify Traveller Process Centre of Visa data alterations (delete/add)
models.readme:
Service Usage

The service provides the ability to notify Traveller Process Centre of Visa data alterations (delete/add)
The search is conducted using a Visa Grant Number.
The Traveller Process Centre is then able to process the Visa Data Information in the Traveller Processing Data Store.
The Visa Grant Number is sent back in the response to user along with Warnings and Information.

Service Behaviour

SV446.1 TRIPS sends Visa add/delete fixed length messages to a new message queue created in the ESB: Message Queue Manager
SV446.2 The ESB instance monitors the queue, converts fixed length messages to a standard XML format and put XML message in a new message queue monitored by the Traveller Processing Centre (TPC).
SV446.3 The TPC processes the message and load data into Traveller Processing Data Store.

Transformation

The ESB instance monitors the queue, converts fixed length messages to a standard XML format and put XML message in a new message queue monitored by the Traveller Processing Centre (TPC).

models.description:
Service Usage

Provides client data retrieval for two modes - summary and detailed - all business dealings for a DIBP client.
models.readme:
Service Usage

Provides client data retrieval for two modes - summary and detailed - all business dealings for a DIBP client.

Summary Mode
Enables BMS to provide DIBP client data (R1 or TIER 1) to external FCC parties in response to an inbound Query 1 (Q1) or NPS NIST file - LEVEL 1 operation. Also used to enable BMS to provide DIBP client data (RR) in response to an inbound Query Reciprocal (QR) - LEVEL 2 operation.
CDH provides the client bio-data for each BMS registered Business Dealing in CDH (via SV540). That is, only for biometric related Business dealings. Also, CDH provides Current Immigration Status data.
RR client data is the same as the R1 data, except it also includes alias and travel doc info and conviction information (but only if that data is associated with a biometrics Business Dealing).
Detailed Mode
Enables BMS to provide additional DIBP client data (R2 OR TIER 2) in response to a follow-up inbound Query 2 (Q2) or Tier 2 request - LEVEL 2 operation.
R2 /TIER 2 provides all the non-biometric related Business dealings for a DIBP client. It also includes additional information (compared with R1) such as travel, conviction information and encounter disposition information.

Service Behaviour

The Retrieve Client Summary and Party Business Dealings service will return a summary of a clients business dealings and related Biodata along with information regarding the clients immigration status.
The Service will consist of a Summary Mode or a Detailed Mode (Determined by a Flag set in the Request message)
The Summary Mode will return the Clients Lawful Status, Biometric Collection Business Dealings and related Biodata
The Detailed Mode will return the Clients Lawful Status, Selected Business Dealings (NOT YET DEFINED) and related biodata and document data

Service Variants

None

Service Flow

Request (BAMS ID)
The inbound Request will contain one or more BAMS IDs. DHub will resolve to the client that the BAMS ID are stored against. Note: BAMS ID is stored on the PARTYSYSTEMIDENTIFIER table linked to the PARTY table

Request (Summary Flag)
If the Summary Flag value is set to True, DHub will return a summary set of data consisting of the Clients Lawful Status, Biometric Collection Business Dealings and related Biodata If the Summary Flag is set to False, DHub will return a detailed set of the Clients Lawful Status, Selected Business Dealings and related biodata and document data

Response - Summary Mode - BiometricEncounterListMsg
All of the clients BAMS IDs will be returned in the response (BiometricEncounterListMsg)

Response - Summary Mode Only - Immigration Status -RetrievePersonBusinessServicesSummaryImmigrationStatusList
DHub will return the Lawful Status from the Person Visa Status table where:
The linking Party System Identifier record (PID) is not ended (ie. does not have an Effective To Timestamp);
The Person Visa Status record is not ended (ie. does not have an Effective To Timestamp);
The Person Visa Status record has the greatest Source Update Timestamp

If a Person Visa Status record does not exist or if one exists however the Lawful Status field is NULL, DHub will not return the RetrievePersonBusinessServicesSummaryImmigrationStatusList

Response - Summary Mode Only - Previous Immigration Status -RetrievePersonBusinessServicesSummaryImmigrationStatusList
DHub will not be returning Previous Immigration Status

Response - Summary Mode Only (Biometric Encounters) RetrievePersonBusinessServicesSummaryDetails
DHub will return all Biometric Enrolments stored against the client (via PartySystemIdentifier records where the Identifier Type Code = BAMS) and the where the Biometric Enrolment record
Has a Biometric Mode Type equal to Finger or Fingerprint and Face

Response - Summary Mode Only (Biometric Encounters) BusinessServiceId
For each Biometric Enrolment the corresponding BAMS ID will be returned (ie PartySystemIdentifier)

Response - Summary Mode Only (Biographic Data) RetrievePersonBusinessServiceSummaryBiographicList
DHub will return each instance of Biographic data linked to the BAMS ID where
The Name Usage type <> 3 (Recorded in Error)

Response - Summary Mode Only (Document Data) RetrievePersonBusinessServiceSummaryDocumentList
DHub will return each instance of Document and Document Biographic data linked to the BAMS ID

Response - Summary Mode (Derogatory Information) RetrievePersonBusinessServiceSummaryDerogatoryInformationList
DHub will not return Derogatory Information in either the Summary or Detailed Mode as this data is not currently stored in DHub

Response - Summary Mode (Biometric Encounter Info) RetrievePersonBusinessServiceSummarySummaryMode

DHub will return the following information for each

  • Biometric Enrolment
  • Biometric Mode
  • Acquisition Location
  • Local Fingerprint Acquisition Date Time
  • UTC Acquisition Date Time Offset
  • Acquisition Reason (Acquisition Reason will be a concat of the values Business Programme Text and Business Event Text)

The service is used to send Expected Movement Record information including the client's Business Service ID, Air/Sea movement information, Biodata, Visa and Travel Document information to the Traveller Processing Centre for performing border clearance.
models.readme:
Service Usage

The service is used to send Expected Movement Record information including the client's Business Service ID, Air/Sea movement information, Biodata, Visa and Travel Document information to the Traveller Processing Centre for performing border clearance.
In response, the Business Service ID is returned along with Information and Warnings.

Service Behaviour

SV598.1 TRIPS sends Expected Movement XML message to a new message queue created in the ESB: Message Queue Manager
SV598.2 The ESB instance monitors the queue and re-route the message to a queue monitored by Traveller Processing Centre
SV598.3 The Traveller Processing Centre processes the message and load data into Traveller Processing Data Store

The service is used for IDH to notify of relevant changes to identities with active traveller business dealings.
models.readme:
Service Usage

The service is used for IDH to notify of relevant changes to identities with active traveller business dealings.
Relevant changes do not include updates to business dealings from other DIBP systems contributing to IDH.

For travellers with active business dealings, Traveller Processing Centre requires notification of updates to the IDH record relating to Travel Documents and Visa Grant status changes.
This data is used at clearance to associate travel documents to movements when travellers check in with one travel document and then present at the primary line with a different travel document.

Service Behaviour

SV599.1 IDH processes an update to biographic and travel document details for an identity record with an active traveller business dealing
SV599.2 IDH will notify Traveller Processing Centre via the ESB

models.description:
Service Usage

The service that provides the ability for Future Traveller to register a movement with IDH as a Business Dealing. This occurs on receipt of Expected Movement (APP/API) from TRIPS. Information in the requested update includes Transborder, Expected and Actual Movement information as well as clearance information ie. risk indicator. It also registers clients of interest or active for Future Traveller.
models.readme:
Service Usage

The service that provides the ability for Future Traveller to register a movement with IDH as a Business Dealing. This occurs on receipt of Expected Movement (APP/API) from TRIPS. Information in the requested update includes Transborder, Expected and Actual Movement information as well as clearance information ie. risk indicator. It also registers clients of interest or active for Future Traveller.
The response for the registration request includes the Business Service ID related to the identity that the IDH resolves the request data.
When a traveller presents at the primary line for clearance, Traveller Processing Centre needs to determine their movement records and associated Treatment Plan. This provides the primary line officer with instructions on how to direct the traveller beyond the primary line. This service is used for cases where a traveller with multiple travel documents presents at the primary line with a different document to that used at check in.

Service Behaviour

SV600.1 TPC sends a message to IDH to create or update Business Dealing records.
SV600.2 Whenever a border clearance transaction is resolved (closed) in TPC, the TPC will send a message to close the Business Dealing record.

This service is used to register and store incoming passenger cards which have been collected from passengers using electronic channels.

This service is used register a submitted passenger card with the provider system. Service Behaviour

The provider system will receive a SV631-RegisterPassengerCard message containing basic passenger card information. The information from the card is then matched to a client and clearance event which is used to enrich the SV631-RegisterPassengerCard payload with various client-related information (identifiers, addresses etc.) and forms the SV632-NotifyPassengerCard notification.

Service Usage

IN009 is an Internal Service that provides the ability to search and retrieve Citizenship Biometric and Biographic data associated with a client's Citizenship Application.
models.readme:
Service Usage

IN009 is an Internal Service that provides the ability to search and retrieve Citizenship Biometric and Biographic data associated with a client's Citizenship Application.
The search is conducted using a Party System Identifier (Citizenship Certificate Number obtained from Orchestration Service).
If a single client is identified and that client has Biometric Enrolment(s), Biographic and Biometric data will be returned in the Response.

Service Behaviour

The service will attempt to retrieve data for a single party based on the supplied criteria, according to the following flow and business rules;
IN009.1 Citizenship Certificate Number ('CCN') will be matched against DOCUMENT.DOCUMENTNUMBER where DOCUMENT.DOCUMENTTYPE in ('CERTIFICATEOFEVIDENCEOFCITIZENSHIP', 'CITIZENSHIP_CERTIFICATE')

IN009.2 Where multiple parties are matched by CCN and Date of Birth is not provided, a response will be sent back with the message PRTY94

IN009.3 Where multiple parties are matched by CCN and Date of Birth is provided, further matching using Date of Birth criteria will take place on any Citizenship Biometric Enrolments as follows - BIOMETRICENROLMENT.BUSINESSCONTEXTTEXT = 'Citizenship', BIOGRAPHIC.BIRTHDATEDAY = Request.CalendarDay, BIOGRAPHIC.BIRTHDATEMONTH = Request.CalendarMonth, BIOGRAPHIC.BIRTHDATE_YEAR = Request.CalendarYear

IN009.4 Where multiple parties have matched on CCN, but none match on Date of Birth, a response will be sent back with the message PRTY00092.

IN009.5 Where no parties match on CCN, a response will be sent back with the message PRTY00091.

IN009.6 Where a single party matches on CCN or on CCN + Date of Birth, a response will be sent back with Biometric Enrolment and Biographic data for the party as follows:BiometricByCitizenship: BiometricCollectionID PSI details of the BAMS ID to which the enrolment is associated, PartySystemIdentifierList PSI details for the party, excluding BiometricCollectionId FacialBiometricAcquiredFlag FACIALBIOMETRICACQUIREDFLAG, BiometricMode BIOMETRICMODETYPE , UTCAcquisitionDatetimeOffset UTCACQUISITIONDATETIMEOFFSET , UTCAcquisitionDatetime LOCALFACIALACQUISITIONTIMESTAMP , AcquistionLocation ACQUISITIONLOCATION , EnrolmentDateTime ENROLMENTTIMESTAMP , BusinessContextType BUSINESSCONTEXTTEXT , BusinessProgramme BUSINESSPROGRAMMETEXT , BusinessEventType BUSINESSEVENTTEXT , EventClassification EVENTCLASSIFICATIONTEXT , ACTProvision ACTPROVISIONTEXT , DocumentNumber , EffectiveFromDateTime EFFECTIVEFROMTIMESTAMP , EffectiveToDateTime EFFECTIVETOTIMESTAMP , SourceSystem, LastUpdated, BiometricByCitizenshipBiographic:, The Biographic details will be taken from a single biographic record chosen on order: nameusagetype, sourceupdatetimestamp, effectiveto_timestamp,BiometricByCitizenshipImageReference

models.description:
Service Usage

This service allows consumers to retrieve a list of all Travel Document details which have been stored by the department for a specified Party. Retrieval of documents will happen at various stages during a visa application process, whenever a Visa Processing Officer views an applicants details.
models.readme:
Service Usage

This service allows consumers to retrieve a list of all Travel Document details which have been stored by the department for a specified Party. Retrieval of documents will happen at various stages during a visa application process, whenever a Visa Processing Officer views an applicants details.

Service Behaviour

Supplied with the 1PartyIdentifier, the service returns Travel Documents stored for that Party. The service will return a list of Document objects.
Consumers may specify a limit and offset for the list, allowing them to slice the data into pages. For example, a limit of 25, with an offset of 0 will return the first 25 results. An offset of 25 will return the next 25. Responses will also contain the total number of documents available.
Consumers may also specify the following criteria:
Document Category -Currently TRAVEL_DOC is the only supported document type for this service.
Document Type - Within Document Categories, there are numerous document types.
The consumer may specify that they wish to retrieve only the latest version of each document, all versions of each document, or the version of each document which was current at a given date and time. The default behaviour is to retrieve all versions.
The service currently only supports travel documents.
The service will return:
Document data
Person Biodata recorded for each document
The size of the set of documents returned by the search, additionally listed by document category.
A count of the available unended documents for the Party Id. Ended documents will not be included in the count.

Service Variants

There are no variants for this service.

Service Composition

This service is not a composite service i.e. it is not composed of other services within the Service Portfolio.
As ISR does not currently support Party Id, the Party Id provided by the consumer must first be looked up in CDH to find an ICSE CID or TRIPS PID which may then be used to retrieve the document list from ISR.
The service relies on the assumption that the identity merge/split notifications from ICSE, which are used to update ISR, are also updating CDH. In other words, if a CID is linked to a PID in CDH, this is a result of an event that has also caused them to be linked in ISR.

Service Flow

  1. Service Consumer invokes service on ESB with RetrieveIdentityDocumentListRequest message
    a. If Party Identifier Type of CDHPARTYID is provided ESB transforms RetrieveIdentityDocumentListRequest to SV288 request to retrieve CID or PID
    b. If PartyIdentifier.IdentifierType = CID or PID do not resolve.

  2. ESB transforms RetrieveIdentityDocumentListRequest to SV288 request to retrieve ICSE CID from CDH.
    i. ESB invokes SV288 with the Party Id provided by the consumer.
    ii. SV288 returns response with all the Party Identifiers stored in CDH fro the given Party Id.
    iii. ESB selects party identifier from SV288 response, in the following order of preference: ICSE CID, TRIPS PID.
    iv. Use AF1 If SV288 does not find a party with the given party id.
    v. Use AF3 If SV288 does not find an ICSE CID or TRIPS PID for the given party id.

  3. ESB creates a RetrieveIdentity request using either the given Party Identifier or the Party Identifier returned in Step 3, and criteria mapped from RetrieveIdentityDocumentListRequest.

  4. ESB invokes ISR.RetrieveIdentity

  5. ISR returns a RetrieveIdentityResponse containing a list of document details, and counts of the available (unended) documents.

  6. ESB transform the RetrieveIdentityResponse message and PartyID into a RetrieveIdentityDocumentListResponse. If no documents are available, a normal RetrieveIdentityDocumentListResponse should be sent to the consumer, with both document count fields set to 0. Use AF2 If the identity is not found.

  7. RetrieveIdentityDocumentListResponse is returned to the Consumer

Alternate Flow 1

A SOAP fault should be returned to the consumer with the MSG-E01 message - no further processing occurs

Alternate Flow 2

A SOAP fault should be returned containing MSG-E02.

Alternate Flow 3

A SOAP fault should be returned to the consumer with the MSG-E04 message - no further processing occurs.

Service State Management Decisions

No state management required.

This service allows consumers to retrieve a list of all Travel Document details which have been stored by the department for a specified Party. Retrieval of documents will happen at various stages during a visa application process, whenever a Visa Processing Officer views an applicants details.

Service Behaviour

Supplied with the 1PartyIdentifier, the service returns Travel Documents stored for that Party. The service will return a list of Document objects.
Consumers may specify a limit and offset for the list, allowing them to slice the data into pages. For example, a limit of 25, with an offset of 0 will return the first 25 results. An offset of 25 will return the next 25. Responses will also contain the total number of documents available.
Consumers may also specify the following criteria:
Document Category -Currently TRAVEL_DOC is the only supported document type for this service.
Document Type - Within Document Categories, there are numerous document types.
The consumer may specify that they wish to retrieve only the latest version of each document, all versions of each document, or the version of each document which was current at a given date and time. The default behaviour is to retrieve all versions.
The service currently only supports travel documents.
The service will return:
Document data
Person Biodata recorded for each document
The size of the set of documents returned by the search, additionally listed by document category.
A count of the available unended documents for the Party Id. Ended documents will not be included in the count.

Service Variants

There are no variants for this service.

Service Composition

This service is not a composite service i.e. it is not composed of other services within the Service Portfolio.
As ISR does not currently support Party Id, the Party Id provided by the consumer must first be looked up in CDH to find an ICSE CID or TRIPS PID which may then be used to retrieve the document list from ISR.
The service relies on the assumption that the identity merge/split notifications from ICSE, which are used to update ISR, are also updating CDH. In other words, if a CID is linked to a PID in CDH, this is a result of an event that has also caused them to be linked in ISR.

Service Flow

  1. Service Consumer invokes service on ESB with RetrieveIdentityDocumentListRequest message
    a. If Party Identifier Type of CDHPARTYID is provided ESB transforms RetrieveIdentityDocumentListRequest to SV288 request to retrieve CID or PID
    b. If PartyIdentifier.IdentifierType = CID or PID do not resolve.

  2. ESB transforms RetrieveIdentityDocumentListRequest to SV288 request to retrieve ICSE CID from CDH.
    i. ESB invokes SV288 with the Party Id provided by the consumer.
    ii. SV288 returns response with all the Party Identifiers stored in CDH fro the given Party Id.
    iii. ESB selects party identifier from SV288 response, in the following order of preference: ICSE CID, TRIPS PID.
    iv. Use AF1 If SV288 does not find a party with the given party id.
    v. Use AF3 If SV288 does not find an ICSE CID or TRIPS PID for the given party id.

  3. ESB creates a RetrieveIdentity request using either the given Party Identifier or the Party Identifier returned in Step 3, and criteria mapped from RetrieveIdentityDocumentListRequest.

  4. ESB invokes ISR.RetrieveIdentity

  5. ISR returns a RetrieveIdentityResponse containing a list of document details, and counts of the available (unended) documents.

  6. ESB transform the RetrieveIdentityResponse message and PartyID into a RetrieveIdentityDocumentListResponse. If no documents are available, a normal RetrieveIdentityDocumentListResponse should be sent to the consumer, with both document count fields set to 0. Use AF2 If the identity is not found.

  7. RetrieveIdentityDocumentListResponse is returned to the Consumer

Alternate Flow 1

A SOAP fault should be returned to the consumer with the MSG-E01 message - no further processing occurs

Alternate Flow 2

A SOAP fault should be returned containing MSG-E02.

Alternate Flow 3

A SOAP fault should be returned to the consumer with the MSG-E04 message - no further processing occurs.

Service State Management Decisions

No state management required.

models.description:
Service Usage

This service allows consumers to register a Travel Document, which will be stored by the department for a specified party.
models.readme:
Service Usage

This service allows consumers to register a Travel Document, which will be stored by the department for a specified party.
The creation of travel documents will happen during every visa application process, as providing travel documents is a requirement of the visa process.

Service Behaviour

To register a travel document the consumer must provide the following mandatory attributes:
EventType.SystemId
EventType.EventClassification
EventType.EventDate
Identifier
Identifier Type
Document Reference Number
Document Type Code
Nationality of Bearer
Once all the travel document information has been entered the system will use the core document attributes (Person Identity, Travel Document Type, Travel Document Number and Nationality of Bearer) to check if the document entered already exists.
There are three scenarios for document registration:
The document already exists and some of the attributes have changed then a new document version is registered in the system.
The document already exists and no attributes have changed, then the document is just linked to a specific event that the document is being used for. An example would be someone entering the country and showing their passport.
The document doesnt exist in the system, therefore a new document entity is registered and a new version of the document entity is registered.
If the document is registered successfully, the service will return:
The ISR Document Id
The ISR Document Version Id
Else if an error occurs the service will return the corresponding error message.

Service Variants

There are no variants for this service.

Service Dependencies

The consumer must have a Party Id, the travel document number and the nationality of the bearer, as mandatory fields when a travel document is being entered.
The provider will identify if a new version or new document entity is required, through the Person Identity, Travel Document Type, Travel Document Number and the Nationality of the Bearer attributes of the Travel Document being entered.

Service Composition

This service is not a composite service i.e. it is not composed of other services within the Service Portfolio.
As ISR does not currently support Party Id, the Party Id provided by the consumer must first be looked up in CDH to find an ICSE CID or TRIPS PID which may then be used to retrieve the document list from ISR.
The service relies on the assumption that the identity merge/split notifications from ICSE, which are used to update ISR, are also updating CDH. In other words, if a CID is linked to a PID in CDH, this is a result of an event that has also caused them to be linked in ISR.

Service Flow

  1. Service Consumer invokes service on ESB with RegisterIdentityDocumentRequest message
  2. If a CID or PID is not used;
    a. ESB transforms RegisterIdentityDocumentRequest to SV288 - Retrieve Consolidated Party Identifiers to retrieve party identifiers from CDH.
    b. ESB invokes SV288 - Retrieve Consolidated Party Identifiers.
    c. ESB returns SV288 - Retrieve Consolidated Party Identifiers response
    d. ESB selects the CID from SV288 if it is returned, else ESB selects PID from SV288 (preference is CID). If SV288 returns an error, then SV146 will return error SV146.MSG-E04 to the consumer - no further processing occurs. Where SV288 returns neither CID nor PID, error code SV146.MSG-E06 is returned to the consumer.
  3. ESB creates a RegisterIdentity request using the chosen identifier (CID or PID), and criteria mapped from RegisterIdentityDocumentRequest.
  4. ESB invokes ISR.RetgisterIdentity
  5. ISR returns a RegisterIdentityResponse containing the full document definition and the ISR Identity Id.
  6. ESB transform the RegisterIdentityResponse message into a RegisterIdentityDocumentResponse returning the ISR Document Id and ISR Document Version Id.
  7. RegisterIdentityDocumentResponse is returned to the Consumer.

Service State Management Decisions

No state management required.

models.description:
Service Usage

This service allows consumers to retrieve person images which have been acquired during a clients involvement with DIBP.
models.readme:
Service Usage

This service allows consumers to retrieve person images which have been acquired during a clients involvement with DIBP.
Currently the only supported image type is FACIAL.
Person images may be retrieved for a number of reasons:
A client arrives at detention centre reception. In order to confirm the clients identity at reception, the latest facial image acquired for the identity claimed by the client is used for visual verification
A person has been tentatively identified based on biographic details as someone already known to DIBP. Further confirmation is needed to determine if the proposed identity matches the subject. An image may be retrieved for purpose of verification.
Detention centres produce bed-check reports four times daily. The reports contain a facial image used to confirm a detainees identity. The latest facial image acquired for that identity appears on the report.
To support the data sharing with the Five Country Conference (FCC) project
Service

Service Behaviour

This service retrieves the latest available person image, which has been acquired by DIBP for a given client and linked to by DIBP to either a CID or PID. All other IDs are supported through SV288 if CID or PID is not known. Alternatively, if an ISR image identifier is supplied it will return the specific image with or without the acquisition profile.
Only images for a Party type of Person are supported. The Organisation party type cannot be associated with a Person Image.
The primary variant of the service uses CID or PID (and optional ISR image id) to locate images. All other IDs that are supported by SV288 (retrieve identifiers) will also be supported by require a call to CDH to resolve these identifiers first. It is therefore strongly recommended that CID or PID is used. If a CID or PID doesnt exist and this is known to the consumer then SV150 should not be required as no facial image will exist.
In addition to the CID, the consumer may optionally provide:
ThumbnailImageFlag, indicating the desired image size. If this flag is not provided, the default will be a full-sized (480x640) image.
The returned image is independent of Business Context. In other words, if the last image recorded for a person was acquired as part of a visa application, this will be the image returned to all consumers of this interface.
The service will return either
A Person Image and
A count of the number of images present in the system and optionally
Image acquisition Profile

Or
A message indicating that no images were found, including a FacialImageCount element set to 0.

Service Variants

None

Service Dependencies

SV288 Retrieve Consolidated Party Identifiers when any other ID but CID or PID is used.

Service Composition

This service is realized through ISR (Primary) service provider.

Service Flow

  1. An event is generated by the Service Consumer which invokes the Retrieve Person Image service on the ESB;
  2. ESB checks for the existence of the PartyIdentifierType of CID or PD. If CID or PID doesnt exist then;
    a. SV288 is invoked to Retrieve all identifiers
    b. If CID or PID exists it is extracted from the SV288 payload
    c. If CID pr PID does not exist then RetrieveImageResponse.xsd with FacialImageCount = 0 is returned to the consumer
  3. ESB transforms the message into the ISR compliant RetrievePersonalIdentifierListRequest.xsd and sends this message to ISR
  4. ISR responds with a RetrievePersonalIdentifierListResponse.xsd and ESB transforms this message into the ESB compliant RetrieveImageResponse.xsd
  5. ESB Sends this RetrieveImageResponse.xsd message to the consumer.
    1.1.1 Alternate Flow 1 (AF1)
    The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the primary provider raises an error.
  6. ESB transforms RetrieveImageResponse Error into Enterprise Error Message.
  7. ESB returns response with Enterprise Error payload.

1.1.2 Alternate Flow 2 (AF2)
If the service call was timeout, ESB should return SV150.MSG-E00 to the consumer.

Service State Management Decisions

No state management required.

models.description:
Service Usage

When an AU search request to another FCC Agency results in a match in that country (Q1/R1 transaction), BMS may, depending upon business logic rules, request additional client information from that FCC Agency (Q2/R2 transaction). Further adhoc client information may also be sought following receipt of the data in R2, using the manually invoked Q3/R3 service.
models.readme:
Service Usage

When an AU search request to another FCC Agency results in a match in that country (Q1/R1 transaction), BMS may, depending upon business logic rules, request additional client information from that FCC Agency (Q2/R2 transaction). Further adhoc client information may also be sought following receipt of the data in R2, using the manually invoked Q3/R3 service.
Note that data is also received as manual Tier 2 data from FCC agencies not yet using SRTP and imported into the BMS. SV548 also provides this data (equivalent to R2 except for some data items) to CDH.
Notify Additional FCC Data for Party service is used by BMS to send this additional data to CDH for storage and display to users via the CSP. The Q3/R3 information is represented as a TRIM reference link for the document which provides the query/response information exchanged for this transaction type. CDH/CSP will retrieve this document from TRIM is requested by an officer accessing the CSP.
The BMS may also receive additional FCC client data for a DIBP client as a result of the QR/RR transaction process. If an inbound Q1 from an FCC Agency has a resulted in a match against a DIBP client record, then the BMS may, depending on business logic rules, send a Query Reciprocal (QR) to that FCC Agency requesting the provision of its details for that client (since the inbound Q1 is anonymous, containing a unique reference ID and fingerprint images only for the client). This additional FCC client data, when received in the Reciprocal Response (RR), is sent by the BMS to the CDH for storage and display to users via the CSP.
Reference to facial image store and doc image store (in the ISR) will also be provided in the service to enable subsequent retrieval from ISR by the CSP is requested by a user.

Service Behaviour

Synchronous service.
Additional FCC client data will be sent to CDH as soon as received. Receipt of all information pertaining to a DIBP client for this FCC search may require several service updates. For example:
(a) Q2/R2 completion for FCC Agency A at Time a
(b) Q2/R2 completion for FCC Agency B at Time b
(c) Q3/R3 first transaction completed for FCC Agency B at time c
(d) Q3/R3 final transaction completed for FCC Agency B at time d.
Note: this service will always include the data sent in a previous notification for a particular client update. That is, full snapshots of data, not incremental updates.

This service is to enable the provider (ICSE, IRIS, CSP) to notify consumer (BAMS) that a client biometrics acquisition is provisionally in error (following manual VPO or IRC provisional error notification in those systems).
BAMS admin support will then be notified following invocation of this service. BAMS will then auto notify this BAMS ID deletion to CDH (which will then update ICSE/IRIS) and ISR. Following biometric acquisition record correction by Admin support, the record will be replayed into BAMS, ISR, CDH and then ICSE/IRIS.

models.readme:
Service Usage

This services allows clients a service to facilitate the biometric matching of a probe image against the data held by DIBP. The initial release will provide facial data matching capability against the biometric data holdings. Additional biographic information could be provided by the client to narrow search results against other, non-biometric data.

Service Behaviour

This service takes in a probe image and matches this probe image against the biometric data holdings of the Department. This will allow clients to undertake a complete gallery search of biometric data in conjunction with optional biographic data to assist with the specificity of the required results. ComparisonLevel acts as a filter and may have one of LOW, MEDIUM, and HIGH. This allows clients to tune the acceptable risk profile of the search. Essentially this also means turning the intended FAR (False Acceptance Rate) and FRR (False Rejection Rate) per search.

Service Usage

This service verifies if the details of an Australian identity document match the records held by the issuing Australian Government authority.
models.readme:
Service Usage

This service verifies if the details of an Australian identity document match the records held by the issuing Australian Government authority.

Service Behaviour

The consumer sends a request with details of the Australian birth certificate to be verified. The request is routed through to the relevant issuing government authority via the Document Verification System (DVS), hosted by Oakton. The issuing authority will send a response status (yes/no/error) which confirms if the details provided match a document held in their records. For all outbound calls, the WSGW will generate the DVS mandated elements VerificationRequestNumber, VersionNumber, VerificationRequestDateTime and VerificationRequestorAgency during the transform into the DVS provider message.

Service Flow

  1. Consumer sends an enterprise SV628 request message to the ESB.
  2. ESB transforms the enterprise message into an internal DVS message.
  3. ESB sends the internal DVS message to the WSGW.
  4. WSGW transforms the internal DVS message into an external DVS message.
  5. WSGW sends the external DVS message to Oakton/DVS.
  6. Oakton respond to the ESB via WSGW with a generic Verification Response message.
  7. The generic response message is transformed into a SV628 response.

Transformation

Transformation exists on the ESB between enterprise and legacy internal DVS messages. The internal DVS messages are transformed into the external DVS messages on the WSGW.

Transformation exists on the ESB between enterprise and legacy internal DVS messages. The internal DVS messages are transformed into the external DVS messages on the WSGW.

models.description:
Service Usage

This service verifies if the details of an Australian identity document match the records held by the issuing Australian Government authority.
models.readme:
Service Usage

This service verifies if the details of an Australian identity document match the records held by the issuing Australian Government authority.

Service Behaviour

The consumer sends a request with details of the Australian Name Change Certificate card to be verified. The request is routed through to the relevant issuing government authority via the Document Verification System (DVS), hosted by Oakton. The issuing authority will send a response status (yes/no/error) which confirms if the details provided match a document held in their records. For all outbound calls, the WSGW will generate the DVS mandated elements VerificationRequestNumber, VersionNumber, VerificationRequestDateTime and VerificationRequestorAgency during the transform into the DVS provider message.

Service Flow

  1. Consumer sends an enterprise SV628 request message to the ESB.
  2. ESB transforms the enterprise message into an internal DVS message.
  3. ESB sends the internal DVS message to the WSGW.
  4. WSGW transforms the internal DVS message into an external DVS message.
  5. WSGW sends the external DVS message to Oakton/DVS.
  6. Oakton respond to the ESB via WSGW with a generic Verification Response message.
  7. The generic response message is transformed into a SV628 response.

Transformation

Transformation exists on the ESB between enterprise and legacy internal DVS messages. The internal DVS messages are transformed into the external DVS messages on the WSGW.

models.readme:
Service Usage

This service is used to initiate biometric matching for a given biometric enrolment within the provider system. The matching function checks for various biometric and biographic mismatches against the enrolment and party.

Service Behaviour

Depending on the data that was registered during the biometric enrolment, the provider system may return none to many match results. A match result willl either be GREEN (No Match/No Adverse Match), AMBER (Pending Match) or RED (Adverse Match). The consumer has the option to set the NotifyResultsFlag element which will invoke SV541-NotifyPersonBiometricsUpdate and notify subscribers with the latest match results.

models.description:
Service Usage

This service is used to initiate biometric referrals to M5 partner countries. A biometric enrolment (enrolled through SV540-NotifyPersonBiometricAcquisition) must exist before referrals can be requested. Enrolments deemed ineligible for referral (eg. Australian citizens) are silently skipped and not referred to M5 partners.
models.readme:
Service Usage

This service is used to initiate biometric referrals to M5 partner countries. A biometric enrolment (enrolled through SV540-NotifyPersonBiometricAcquisition) must exist before referrals can be requested. Enrolments deemed ineligible for referral (eg. Australian citizens) are silently skipped and not referred to M5 partners.

Service Behaviour

The provider will initiate biometric referrals to M5 partners based on the BiometricReferralMode specified in the payload. "MANUAL" mode will send referrals to the M5 partners specified in the payload. "AUTOMATIC" mode will send referrals to M5 partners determined by risk rules applied to the enrolment. "REVALIDATE" mode will refer the enrolment to the M5 partners who previously received a referral for this enrolment.

For each referral, the provider will invoke a SV542-NotifyPersonBiometricMatchResults to notify subscribers that an M5 referral is pending. Upon receiving a response from the M5 partners, a subsequent SV542 notification is sent with the match result. Additional business dealing information returned from partners may also be notified in SV548-NotifyPersonForeignBusinessServicesSummary.

Service Usage

This service provides a direct service call to Security Referral Service (SRS) to create an SRS request.
models.readme:
Service Usage

This service provides a direct service call to Security Referral Service (SRS) to create an SRS request.
The creation of a security referral will occur during the visa application process within GVP.

Service Behaviour

This service provides a response to be returned to GVP. In the case that a referral creates a positive response, the response will also include the SRS referralID. Any errors that occur during the operation of this service will be communicated to GVP in a response message.

Service Variants

There are no variants for this service

Service Dependencies

There are no dependencies for this service

Service Composition

The primary provider is the SRS System.

This service is not a composite service i.e. it is not composed of other services within the Service Portfolio.

Service Flow

  1. An event is generated by GVP using source system specific referral data.
  2. Sv339 Register Applicant Security Referral is invoked, assembling the group of messages into a single request in the GVP source system format.
  3. ESB invokes the primary provider SRS as follows:
    a. ESB will transform RegisterApplicantSecurityReferralRequest.xml into PerfomSecurityReferralRequest.xml as per data mappings in the DIMADCD d15 Service Specification - SV339 - v01.0 RegisterApplicantSecurityReferral.xls micro design spreadsheet. b. SRS executes this service PerfomSecurityReferralRequest.xml and returns PerfomSecurityReferralResponse.xml to the ESB. c. ESB transforms PerfomSecurityReferralResponse.xml into RegisterApplicantSecurityReferralResponse.xml as per data mappings in the DIMADCD d15 Service Specification - SV339 - v01.0 RegisterApplicantSecurityReferral.xls micro design spreadsheet.
  4. ESB returns RegisterApplicantSecurityReferralResponse.xml to the consumer (GVP)
    1.1.1 Alternate Flow 1 (AF1)
    The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the primary provider raises an error.

1.1.2 Alternate Flow 2 (AF2)
If the ESB raises an error before or while attempting to contact the primary provider, it will respond to the consumer with the relevant Enterprise Error payload. See section 4 of this document for a full listing of Return Codes and Messages.

Service State Management Decisions

If the provider system returns an error code at any stage of the service execution, the message flow will be stopped and the error returned to the consumer. This service will not return partial response messages.
