models.description:
Service Usage

This service is used to retrieve details of a specific Note returned from the current data model in ICSE which indicates that notes are stored as events and as additional info items in ICSE. The notes subset to be retrieved have been agreed on by GSM and ICSE as appropriate for this service. This service may be consumed at any time. The only requirements are that the note id is passed to this service. The note Id is a compound key based upon the ICSE/GSM concept that a unique note can be chosen by a combination ICSE Key fields which will be expressed as a single hyphen delimited string in the service and when exposed to GSM. However, when used to interface with ICSE services it will be expressed in its individual key components.
models.readme:
Service Usage

This service is used to retrieve details of a specific Note returned from the current data model in ICSE which indicates that notes are stored as events and as additional info items in ICSE. The notes subset to be retrieved have been agreed on by GSM and ICSE as appropriate for this service. This service may be consumed at any time. The only requirements are that the note id is passed to this service. The note Id is a compound key based upon the ICSE/GSM concept that a unique note can be chosen by a combination ICSE Key fields which will be expressed as a single hyphen delimited string in the service and when exposed to GSM. However, when used to interface with ICSE services it will be expressed in its individual key components.

Service Behaviour

This service provides the following behaviour:
A consumer of this service provides:
Note Id
A consumer of this service receives:
Note Details which consist of
Note Text

The following notes types are returned in this service.
Event Notes
Assessment Notes
Permission Request Additional Info Notes
Any Audit information that is associated with the Activity and its associated activity notes.

Service Variants

None

Service Dependencies

None

Service Composition

This is not a composite service.

Service Flow

A normal flow for this service is to have the SV199 Retrieve Note Details Request called by the portal. SV199- Retrieve Note Details then calls the ICSE corresponding Retrieve Note Service. ICSE will then execute the Retrieve Note Details request and return a response message back to SV 199. This in turn is returned to the consumer.
SV199 has a Note Id key that is a compound key.
The key definition is located in the SV199 micro document.
The detail of this flow is as follows:
Service consumer invokes service SV199 on ESB using RetrieveNoteDetailsRequest.
Service SV199 then breaks up the noteId into the previously mentioned ICSE keys and creates an ICSE Request message.
Service SV199 invokes ICSE sending a request message.
ICSE receives the request and processes the Retrieve Note Details Request.
ICSE then sends a message back to service SV199.
Service SV199 sends a response message to the consumer.
Alternate Flow 1
The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when SV199 returns an error.
Service consumer invokes service SV199 on ESB using RetrieveNoteDetailsRequest.
Service SV199 then breaks up the noteId into the previously mentioned ICSE keys and creates an ICSE Request message.
Service SV199 invokes ICSE sending a request message.
ICSE receives the request and encounters an error.
ICSE then sends an error message back to service SV199.
SV199 detects the error and transforms ICSE Error into Enterprise Error
SV199 passes a response with this Enterprise Error to the consumer.

Service State Management Decisions

No state management required.

models.description:
Service Usage

This service allows the user to modify specific information on a visa application.
models.readme:
Service Usage

This service allows the user to modify specific information on a visa application.
The execution of this service is a step that is likely to occur when a Visa Processing Officer (VPO) is required to update an application because a party has had a change of circumstances and this must be reflected in the Visa Application.
The service updates details for a specific Visa Application. The service will only deliver information which has actually changed to the backend systems, and not the entire data set.

Service Behaviour

The service updates details for a specific Visa Application. The service will only deliver information (including context) which has actually changed to the backend systems, and not the entire data set.
This service provides the following behaviour:
Checks the user initiating this business function is authorised to modify the visa application
Modifies Visa Application specific information
Modifies Visa Applicant specific information
Allows for the creation of notes specific to the Visa Application or Visa Applicant.
Allows adding new Applicants to a Visa Application.
Allows changing the association to the primary Visa Applicant and or role type
Follows an all or nothing principal for updates. This means if any particular part of the update is unable to be performed, then nothing will be updated.

The following chapters describe in detail what data types the consumer can manipulate and how the service interface is structured.
Note regarding concurrency: The current version of this service allows concurrent updates of the same data records in ICSE and thus it doesnt guarantee data consistency.
1.1.1 Data Types which can be manipulated by this service
SV012 allows manipulating the following CDM data types and operations:
Updating, Inserting and Deleting of Single Attributes of Visa Application or Visa Applicant
Updating, Inserting and Deleting of Child Objects of Visa Application or Visa Applicant
Inserting of Notes (Notes Portal, Client Notes and Case Notes)
Updating of Person Visa Application Role And Or Association
Inserting/deleting of Visa Applicants

The handling of the different data types is described in the following chapters.
1.1.1.1 Child Objects of Visa Application and Visa Applicant
If the Consumer intends to update, insert or delete Child Objects (which are the CDM representation of ICSE events) it needs to provide the following data

CDM Identifier for the Child Object (in case of UPDATE and DELETE)
Operation (UPDATE, INSERT or DELETE)
Fully populated Child with all related Attributes (in case of UPDATE and INSERT)

Remark: SV012 allows updating, inserting and deleting of multiple Child Objects, Attributes and Notes at the same time in a single transaction.
1.1.1.1 Single Attributes of Visa Application or Visa Applicant
If the Consumer intends to update, insert or delete an attribute (which is the CDM representation of an ICSE PermissionRequestInfo) of the Visa Application or Visa Applicant it needs to provide the following data:
ICSE Sequence number if the attribute has an ICSE Multiplicity > 1 (in case of DELETE and UPDATE)
CDM Attribute with its new value (in case of UPDATE and INSERT)
SV012 applies the following logic to determine which operation (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE) the consumer intends to have processed:

Seq Number is present Value is present, i.e., node is not nil. Operation
n/a yes UPDATE or INSERT
n/a no DELETE
Table 1: Determine the operation of Single Attributes with multiplicity = 1

Seq Number is present Value is present, i.e., node is not nil. Operation
no yes INSERT
yes no DELETE
yes yes UPDATE=DELETE +INSERT
Table 2: Determine the operation of Single Attributes with multiplicity > 1

In the case of UPDATE for multiplicity > 1, first the DELETE operation has to be performed followed by INSERT.
1.1.1.2 Inserting Notes
If the Consumer intends to insert a Note (Notes Portal, Client Notes or Case Notes) it needs to provide the following data:
For Notes Portal
Application ID
AssociationType (In ICSE terms this represents a Qualifier)
Mandatory AssociationId (This is stored in ICSE as EventAdditionalInfo)
Complete Notes Context

For Case Notes
Application ID
Complete Notes Context

For Client Notes
Application ID
Applicant ID
Role
Complete Notes Context
SV012 allows only inserting notes. Deletes und Updates of Notes are not possible.

Remark: SV012 allows inserting of notes and inserting, updating and deleting of child objects and attributes at the same time in one transaction.
1.1.1.3 Updating Role and or association to primary applicant
If the Consumer intends to update the association to the primary applicant and or Role it needs to provide the following data:
Application ID
Applicant ID
Current Role
New Role (Required for update of role)
Association details (Required for update of association)
SV012 allows only updating the role and or association of a Visa Applicant. Inserts and deletes are not possible as it assumes update of role for applicants already present in the application. Even if only update of role is intended, association details are also mandatory to be sent. For only update of association to primary applicant, new role need not be sent. For update of both association and role, all the above mentioned fields are required to be sent.
Restriction: If the consumer intends to change the Role of a Visa Applicant and to change the association, the service call does not allow changes to other data elements at the same time.
1.1.1.4 Inserting/deleting Visa Applicants
If the consumer intends to insert/delete a client it needs to provide the following data:
Application ID
Applicant ID
Role
Restriction: If the consumer intends to insert/delete clients, the service does not allow any other data manipulations at the same time.

1.1.2 Choice Groups
The XSD of SV012 contains a choice group element in order to provide a structured interface to the consumer. The choice group element allows one of the following children
ModifyVisaApplicationOrApplicantDetails
ModifyApplicant
These children are of complex type and contain all variant specific Elements.
1.1.2.1 ModifyVisaApplicationOrApplicantDetails
This choice group provides the ability to update, insert and delete one or many data items belonging to a Visa Application or Visa Applicant(s). Data consists of information from any of the following CDM Subject Areas:
Visa Application
Follow up Alerts
Person Visa Applicant
GSM Person Visa Application
Person Visa Application Claim
ASCO Code
Party Relationship
Regional Australian Address
Person Factors (Employment, Language, Police Check, Country Stay, Qualification)
Values Statement
Notes (Portal Notes, Case Notes and Client notes)
No Adverse Information
1.1.2.2 ModifyApplicant
This choice group allows adding new Applicants to a Visa Application, modifying the association of a particular Applicant to the primary Applicant, and or change the role of the Visa Applicant.
1.1.3 Response Message
A consumer of this service receives either:
An Enterprise Service Acknowledgement, or
An Enterprise Error if the Visa Application cannot be modified for whatever reason.

Service Dependencies

A Visa Application must be existent in the provider system.

Service Composition

There is no composition call.

Service Flow

In general this service processes incoming requests in 2 steps

  1. The service creates a message dependent on which element of the choice group is filled and what operation the consumer intends to process.
  2. Sending the request message to ICSE
    The following chapters describe the behaviour of the service for each element of the choice group differently.
    1.1.1 ModifyVisaApplicationOrApplicantDetails
    1.1.1.1 Service Flow for ModifyApplicantOrApplicantDetails
    The service receives the request message from the consumer. The Message can contain single Attributes (ICSE: Permission Request Infos), Child Objects of the Visa Application (ICSE: Events) and Notes (either Notes Portal or Case Notes).

Based to some rules (see Chapter 1.2.1 Data Types which can be manipulated by this service) the Flow determines the operation (Delete, Update and Insert) for each element. Then the Flow sends an accordingly populated ApplicationMaintenanceRequest message to ICSE. ICSE will then execute this request and return an acknowledgement message back to service SV012 where a response message is returned to the consumer.

The detail of this flow is as follows:

  1. Service consumer invokes service SV012 on ESB using ModifyVisaApplicationRequest.
  2. SV012 creates an ICSE request message according to the rules described in chapter 2.1 (ICSE Service Provider).
    a. For each single Attribute a PermissionRequestInfo-Element is created.
    b. For each Child Object at least one Event-Element is created.
    c. For each Note one Event-Element is created.
  3. Service SV012 invokes ICSE sending the request message.
  4. ICSE receives the request and tries to processes the updates for the specified visa application or the specified Visa Applicant(s).
  5. ICSE then sends an acknowledgement message back to service SV012.
  6. Service SV012 sends a successful response message to the consumer.
    1.1.1.2 Alternate Flow 2
    The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when ICSE returns an error.
  7. Service consumer invokes service SV012 on ESB using ModifyVisaApplicationRequest.
  8. SV012 creates an ICSE request message according to the rules described in chapter 2.1 (ICSE Service Provider).
    a. For each single Attribute a PermissionRequestInfo-Element is created.
    b. For each Child Object at least one Event-Element is created.
    c. For each Note one Event-Element is created.
  9. Service SV012 invokes ICSE sending the request message.
  10. ICSE receives the request and encounters an error.
  11. SV012 detects the error and transforms ICSE Error into Enterprise Error
  12. SV012 passes a response with this Enterprise Error to the consumer.
    1.1.2 ModifyApplicant
    1.1.2.1 Service Flow for ModifyApplicant
    The service receives the request message from the consumer. The Message contains the either a request to modify the association to the primary Visa Applicant or to modify the role of a Visa Applicant or to modify both the association to the primary Visa Applicant and the role of a Visa Applicant and/or to add a new Applicant to a Visa Application.

Then the Flow sends an accordingly populated ApplicationMaintenanceRequest message to ICSE. Dependent on which element of the choice group is passed by the consumer different elements of the ApplicationMaintenanceRequest are populated:
o In case of ModifyApplicantAssociationAndOrRoleType the UpdateClntRole Element with both children (oldclnt and updtclnt) is populated.
o In case of AddNewApplicant the AddClntRole Element is populated.

ICSE will then execute this request and return an acknowledgement message back to service SV012 where a response message is returned to the consumer.

The detail of this flow is as follows:

  1. Service consumer invokes service SV012 on ESB using ModifyVisaApplicationRequest.
  2. SV012 creates a ICSE request message
  3. SV012 invokes ICSE sending the request message.
  4. ICSE receives the request and tries processes the updates for the specified visa application or the specified Visa Applicant(s).
  5. ICSE then sends an acknowledgement message back to service SV012.
  6. Service SV012 sends a successful response message to the consumer.
    1.1.2.2 Alternate Flow 1
    The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when CDH returns an error.
  7. Service consumer invokes service SV012 on ESB using ModifyVisaApplicationRequest.
  8. SV012 receives the Enterprise Error and passes a response with this Enterprise Error to the consumer
    1.1.2.3 Alternate Flow 2
    The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when ICSE returns an error.
  9. Service consumer invokes service SV012 on ESB using ModifyVisaApplicationRequest.
  10. SV012 creates a ICSE request message
  11. SV012 invokes ICSE sending the request message.
  12. ICSE receives the request and encounters an error.
  13. SV012 detects the error and transforms ICSE Error into Enterprise Error
  14. SV012 passes a response with this Enterprise Error to the consumer.

Transformation

To see the latest message mappings refer to the Micro Design document DIMA_DCD d15 Service Specification - SV012 - v03.0 Modify Visa Application.xls
Specific mappings required:
1) Retrieving ICSE Reversal event type codes from ICSE event type codes. ESB code mapping table to be used for this.
2) Retrieving ICSE Qualifier code from ICSE event type code and Portal reason type codes. ESB code mapping table to be used for this.
3) Mapping required for transforming EmploymentVerificationStatus, EmploymentVerifiedFlag under Employment History, to one ICSE field which then gets stored. The combination of the two fields determines which value to be sent to ICSE.

Service State Management Decisions

No state management required.

models.description:
Service Usage

This service is used by the consumer to create a referral for a specific applicant in a visa application.
models.readme:
Service Usage

This service is used by the consumer to create a referral for a specific applicant in a visa application.
A referral is a request from one DIAC work area to another to undertake some activity, for a specific purpose related to the processing of an application.

Service Behaviour

The consumer of this service will provide:
Visa Application ID
Party ID of the specific applicant for whom the referral is being created
The type of referral
The status of the referral
The method of transfer
The reason for the referral
Reference ID of the supporting document
Notes applicable for an officer processing the referral
Reference ID of the scanned/digitised documents
This service will record the referral details, generate its unique identifier (referral request ID) and link it to the given visa application ID.
A consumer of this service receives either:
Unique Identifier of the referral and its status

Or
An Enterprise Error detailing why create was unsuccessful.

Service Variants

This service has no service variants.

Service Dependencies

This service relies on the consumer already having a unique identifier of a Visa Application as a Visa Application Id.

Service Composition

There is no Composition call.

Service Flow

The following service flow describes a successful execution path.

  1. The Consumer invokes the service on ESB.
  2. Consumer provides ICSE ClientId to call ICSE otherwise Service throw Exception.
  3. ESB validate request data.
  4. ESB invokes service provider ICSE for Create Visa Application Referral.
  5. ICSE returns the Referral Request Id and sequence number of the newly created Visa Application referral to ESB.
  6. ESB transforms ICSE response into CreateVisaApplicationReferralResponse.
  7. ESB returns CreateVisaApplicationReferralResponse to Consumer.

1.1.1 Alternate Flow 1
The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the primary provider (ICSE) raises an error.

  1. The Consumer invokes the service on ESB.
  2. ESB validate request data.
  3. Consumer provides ICSE ClientId to call ICSE otherwise Service throw Exception.
  4. ESB invokes service provider ICSE for Create Visa Application Referral.
  5. ICSE returns response to ESB.
  6. ESB detects that ICSE has returned an error.
  7. ESB transforms ICSE error into Enterprise Error Message.
  8. ESB returns response with Enterprise Error payload to Consumer.

1.1.2 Alternate Flow 3
The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when ESB data validation fails.

  1. The Consumer invokes the service on ESB.
  2. ESB validate request data.
  3. ESB found some data not as expected or not match.
  4. ESB transforms the validation error into Enterprise Error Message.
  5. ESB returns response with Enterprise Error payload to Consumer.

The following tables are to be used by ESB to validate the data of consumer request for: Referral Reason, Referral Types, and Referral Method of Transfer.

models.description:
Service Usage

The Retrieve Person Visa History service is to be used to retrieve specific information pertaining to a Person. GVP will be the initial consumer of this Service in a SfP11 timeframe, and is available for consumption by additional consumers within DIAC.
models.readme:
Service Usage

The Retrieve Person Visa History service is to be used to retrieve specific information pertaining to a Person. GVP will be the initial consumer of this Service in a SfP11 timeframe, and is available for consumption by additional consumers within DIAC.

Service Behaviour

The Response Visa History details provided in this service include attributes within the business object:
Visa
Travel Document
Associated Evidence
Associated Name

The service uses TRIPS as the primary source of Visa Grants, however is supplemented by ICSE for the VisaConditionCodes in the event that TRIPS does not hold the complete set of VisaConditionCode information (applicable to those Visas created pre: SfP11)

This service is designed to be called for a Person where details regarding Visa History are required. The request filter enables the service to limit the Response based on Visas within a specific time period or the last in effect Visa for the Person. This service supplements the summary view provided in SV277 and SV278. In all cases, the maximum number of Visas returned will be 60.

Service Variants

None

Service Dependencies

None

Service Composition

This service is a non composite service when a PID is provided within the Service Request.
This service is a composite service, i.e. composed of other services within the Service Portfolio, when an alternate Party Identifier is provided by the consumer. In this event, this service engages Sv288 Retrieve Consolidated Party Identifiers to retrieve the required PID for the request call to TRIPS.

Service Flow

  1. An event is generated by the Service Consumer which invokes the Retrieve Person Visa History service on the ESB;
    a) If GVP provides the PID, the ESB will pass the PID direct to TRIPS
    b) If GVP provides the alternate Party Identifiers, e.g. CID , CDHPARTYID, the ESB engages Sv288 Retrieve Consolidated Party Identifiers to retrieve the applicable PID.

  2. ESB transforms the eXML to Flat File taking only the following from the eXML payload:
    PartyIdentifier - If only this parameter is present all visas, up to a maximum of 60, will be returned in reverse chronological sequence. Visas with all statuses will be returned.
    If applicable, the following RequestFilter will be invoked:
    Option 1:
    StartDate - If this parameter is present by the user, TRIPS will return all visas for the person with a granted date greater than or equal to 'Date from' in reverse chronological sequence up to a maximum of 60 visas. Visas with all statuses will be returned.
    EndDate - present date

    Option 2: LastInEffectVisaFlag -

  3. TRIPS Retrieve Visa API is invoked passing in the PartyIdentifier.

  4. TRIPS Retrieve Visa API replies with a Flat File.

  5. ESB transforms the Flat File to eXML and supplements the eXML with Descriptions from the TRIPS codes supplied. These will be both lookups and a hardcoded set of values.

  6. ESB Replies to the consumer with the eXML message RetrievePersonVisaHistoryResponse.xml.

1.1.1 Alternate Flow 1 (AF1)
Alternate Flow 1 (AF1): RetrieveVisaSystemOfRecordFlag false.
Where TRIPS is the system of record for the complete set of Visa Conditions, the Visa conditions will be retrieved from TRIPS. In the cases that TRIPS does not hold the complete set of Visa Conditions, ICSE will be invoked to retrieve mandatory condition codes.
The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the PartyIdentifier retrieves a Visa that is an ICSE supplemented Visa.

  1. An event is generated by the Service Consumer which invokes the Retrieve Person Visa History service on the ESB;

  2. ESB transforms the eXML to Flat File taking only the PersonalIdentifier from the eXML payload.

  3. TRIPS Retrieve Visa API is invoked passing in the PersonalIdentifier.

  4. TRIPS Retrieve Visa API replies with a Flat File.

  5. ESB transforms the Flat File to eXML and supplements the eXML with Descriptions from the TRIPS codes supplied. These will be both lookups and a hardcoded set of values.

  6. ESB inspects each Visa Grant Number from the TRIPS Response message
    If the RetrieveVisaSystemOfRecordFlag indicates false, AND if the VisaCriteriaSatisfiedCode is P or S, the system shall invoke ICSE as per item 7 & 8 below.

  7. ESB creates an ICSE request message RetrieveMandConditionsRequest.xml using multiple Visa Grant Number, VisaCriteriaSatisfiedCode, LodgementLocationType, VisaStatisticalCode, GrantDate, VisaClassCode, VisaSubClassCode, and User ID as inputs.

  8. In the event that there exists multiple Visas, the ESB will include the multiple visa details (Visa Grant Number, VisaCriteriaSatisfiedCode, LodgementLocationType, VisaStatisticalCode, GrantDate, VisaClassCode, VisaSubClassCode, and User ID), maximum of 60, within the one RetrieveMandConditionsRequest.xml.

  9. ICSE Response message RetrieveMandConditionsResponse.xml is passed back to the ESB. The Response message will include the VisaGrantNumber and MandatoryConditionCode per one Visa.
    (1) RetrieveMandConditionsResponse.xml will not include any VisaGrantNumber when a MandatoryConditionCode does not exist.
    (2) In the event that the data provided to ICSE within the RetrieveMandConditionsRequest.xml (Visa Grant Number, VisaCriteriaSatisfiedCode, LodgementLocationType, VisaStatisticalCode, GrantDate, VisaClassCode, VisaSubClassCode, and User ID) does not match the information stored in ICSE, ICSE will produce an error in the RetrieveMandConditionsResponse.xml advising the VisaGrantNumber and the applicable error. Note: This will result in a warning from ESB, however the service will not fail.

  10. In the event that multiple Visa details exist, ICSE will return the VisaGrantNumber and MandatoryConditionCode (or error message if applicable), per one Visa

  11. ESB matches the MandatoryConditionCode with the VisaGrantNumber and supplements the TRIPS response with these codes merging all data.

  12. ESB Replies to the consumer with the eXML message RetrievePersonVisaHistoryResponse.xml, to a maximum of 60, will be returned.

1.1.2 Alternate Flow 3 (AF3)

The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the TRIPS request fails.

  1. An event is generated by the Service Consumer which invokes the Retrieve Person Visa History service on the ESB;
  2. ESB transforms the eXML to Flat File taking only the PersonalIdentifier from the eXML payload.
  3. TRIPS Retrieve Visa API is invoked passing in the PersonalIdentifier.
  4. TRIPS Retrieve Visa API replies with a Flat File as an error code.
  5. ESB inspects the error, maps if able and returns an ESB SOAP Fault to the consumer with the error code and description.
    1.1.3 Alternate Flow 4 (AF4)
    The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the ICSE request fails.
  6. An event is generated by the Service Consumer which invokes the Retrieve Person Visa History service on the ESB;
  7. ESB transforms the eXML to Flat File taking only the PersonalIdentifier from the eXML payload.
  8. TRIPS Retrieve Visa API is invoked passing in the PersonalIdentifier.
  9. TRIPS Retrieve Visa API replies with a Flat File.
  10. ESB transforms the Flat File to eXML and supplements the eXML with Descriptions from the TRIPS codes supplied. These will be both lookups and a hardcoded set of values.
  11. ESB inspects the Visa Grant Number from the TRIPS Response message
    a. If the RetrieveVisaSystemOfRecordFlag indicates false, AND if the VisaCriteriaSatisfiedCode is P or S, the system shall invoke ICSE as per item 7 & 8 below.
  12. In the event that there exists multiple Visas, the ESB will include the multiple visa details (Visa Grant Number, VisaCriteriaSatisfiedCode, LodgementLocationType, VisaStatisticalCode, GrantDate, VisaClassCode, VisaSubClassCode, and User ID), maximum of 60 , within the one RetrieveMandConditionsRequest.xml.
  13. ICSE Response message RetrieveMandConditionsResponse.xml is passed back to the ESB. The Response message will include the VisaGrantNumber and MandatoryConditionCode per one Visa.
  14. RetrieveMandConditionsResponse.xml will not include any VisaGrantNumber when a MandatoryConditionCode does not exist.
  15. In the event that the data provided to ICSE within the RetrieveMandConditionsRequest.xml (Visa Grant Number, VisaCriteriaSatisfiedCode, LodgementLocationType, VisaStatisticalCode, GrantDate, VisaClassCode, VisaSubClassCode, and User ID) does not match the information stored in ICSE, ICSE will produce an error in the RetrieveMandConditionsResponse.xml advising the VisaGrantNumber and the applicable error.
  16. In the event that there is a security error, the ICSE Response message RetrieveMandConditionsResponse.xml is passed back to the ESB displaying the appropriate code e.g. 10021, 10002, 10004
  17. In the event that the data provided to ICSE within the RetrieveMandConditionsRequest.xml (Visa Grant Number, VisaCriteriaSatisfiedCode, LodgementLocationType, VisaStatisticalCode, GrantDate, VisaClassCode, VisaSubClassCode, and User ID) does not match the information stored in ICSE, ICSE will produce an error in the RetrieveMandConditionsResponse.xml advising the VisaGrantNumber and the applicable error. Note: This will result in a warning from ESB, however the service will not fail.
  18. ESB inspects the error, maps if able and returns an ESB SOAP Fault to the consumer with the error code and description.

Service State Management Decisions

RetrieveVisaSystemOfRecordFlag is true, indicates that TRIPS is the source of record for all Visa Conditions.
RetrieveVisaSystemOfRecordFlag is false, indicates that TRIPS is not the source of record for all Visa Conditions, and therefore ICSE will be invoked to retrieve mandatory conditions applicable to that Visa.

models.description:
Service Usage

This service allows a consumer to retrieve all visa application referrals details, as specified by the Visa Application ID, all the referrals included within it and notes history summaries.
models.readme:
Service Usage

This service allows a consumer to retrieve all visa application referrals details, as specified by the Visa Application ID, all the referrals included within it and notes history summaries.
This service also allows a consumer to retrieve a specific visa application referrals details, as specified by the Visa Application ID and Referral Id, and notes history details.
The execution of this service is a step that is likely to occur when a consumer wants to view the referrals information pertaining to a visa application.

Service Behaviour

A consumer of this service provides:
Unique identifier of the visa application and, optionally, a unique identifier of the referral
A consumer of this service receives either:
Data consisting of a subset of information from the following CDM Subject Areas:
o Party
o Referral
o Note

Or
An Enterprise Error detailing why the retrieve was unsuccessful.

Service Variants

This service has no service variants.

Service Dependencies

This service relies on the consumer already having a unique identifier of a Visa Application as a Visa Application Id. The service also relies on the consumer providing the unique identifier of the referral when required for retrieving notes history details

Service Composition

This service is a composite service. It is composed of service SV176 (Transform Identifier) within the Service Portfolio.

Service Flow

The following service flow describes a successful execution path.
Service Consumer invokes service on ESB.
ESB transforms RetrieveVisaApplicationReferralRequest into ICSE XML and sends it to ICSE.
ICSE executes CICS transaction and returns ICSE XML to ESB.
ESB transforms ICSE XML into RetrieveVisaApplicationReferralResponse. (Enterprise Acknowledgement)
ESB check RetrieveVisaApplicationReferralResponse for the returned clientId(s) -then call SV176 (Transform Identifier) to retrieve the partyId(s) for this given clientId(s) and use the partyId(s) in the response.
ESB returns RetrieveVisaApplicationReferralResponse to Consumer.

1.1.1 Alternate Flow 1
The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the primary provider (ICSE) raises an error.

  1. Service Consumer invokes service on ESB.
  2. ESB transforms RetrieveVisaApplicationReferralRequest into ICSE XML and invokes service provider ICSE.
  3. ICSE executes CICS transaction and returns ICSE XML to ESB.
  4. ESB detects that ICSE has returned an error and constructs corresponding SOAP fault segment.
  5. ESB transforms ICSE Error into Enterprise Error Message.
  6. ESB returns response with Enterprise Error payload.

1.1.2 Alternate Flow 2
The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the service SV176 raises an error.

  1. Service Consumer invokes service on ESB.
  2. ESB transforms RetrieveVisaApplicationReferralRequest into ICSE XML and sends it to ICSE.
  3. ICSE executes CICS transaction and returns ICSE XML to ESB.
  4. ESB transforms ICSE XML into RetrieveVisaApplicationReferralResponse. (Enterprise Acknowledgement)
  5. ESB check RetrieveVisaApplicationReferralResponse for the returned clientId -then call SV176 (Transform Identifier) to retrieve the partyId for this given clientId.
  6. ESB detects that SV176 has returned an error and constructs corresponding SOAP fault segment.
  7. ESB transforms SV176 Error into Enterprise Error Message.
  8. ESB returns response with Enterprise Error payload.

Service State Management Decisions

No state management required.

Transformation

The ESB transforms the NotifyBusinessTravelCardApplicationRequest.xsd message differently, depending on the request payload.

If the request is for an application creation (NotifyABTCCreate element exists), the message is transformed into a CreateApplicationExtendedRequest.xsd ABTC provider message.

If the request is for a passport update (NotifyABTCUpdatePassport element exists), the message is transformed into a UpdatePassportRequest.xsd ABTC provider message.

models.readme:
Service Usage

This service would bring all the receipt and payment related details for a selected receipt.
Note:
This service doesnt search for any payment made for e-Visa related application.

Service Behaviour

The consumer of this service would provide receipt number which needs to be sent to provider system.
In a successful operation, the consumer will receive receipt details and payment details related to the receipt.

Service Variants

None

Service Dependencies

ICSE

Service Composition

This service is not a composite service.

Service Flow

  1. An event is generated by the Service Consumer which invokes the RetrieveReceipt service on the ESB.
  2. ESB sends RetrieveReceiptRequest to ICSE.
  3. ICSE returns RetrieveReceiptResponse to ESB.
  4. Use AF2 if ICSE request is timeout.
  5. ESB examines the Response Messages within RetrieveReceiptResponse to determine whether there is any error returned by ICSE, if so, use AF1.
  6. ESB returns list of payment receipts or error message to Service Consumer.

1.1.1.1 Alternate Flow 1 (AF1)
The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the primary provider (ICSE) raises an error.

  1. ESB transforms ICSE Error into Enterprise Error Message.
  2. ESB returns response with Enterprise Error payload.

Potential Response Message Labels
SV142.MSG-E01 - User does not have permission to Retrieve Receipt Details
1.1.1.2 Alternate Flow 2 (AF2)
If the service call was timeout, ESB should return SV142.MSG-E02 to the consumer.

Service State Management Decisions

No state management required.

Or
An Enterprise Error detailing why modify was unsuccessful.

Service Variants

This service has no service variants.

Service Dependencies

This service relies on the consumer already having a unique identifier of a Visa Application as a Visa Application Id and a referral have been created.

Service Composition

Service Flow

The following service flow describes a successful execution path.

The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the primary provider (ICSE) raises an error.

  1. The Consumer invokes the service on ESB.
  2. Consumer provides ICSE ClientId to call ICSE otherwise Service throw Exception.
  3. ESB invokes service provider ICSE for Modify Visa Application Referral.
  4. ICSE returns response to ESB.

Service State Management Decisions

models.description:
Service Usage

This service is used to retrieve details of a specific Note returned from the current data model in ICSE which indicates that notes are stored as events and as additional info items in ICSE. The notes subset to be retrieved have been agreed on by GSM and ICSE as appropriate for this service. This service may be consumed at any time. The only requirements are that the note id is passed to this service. The note Id is a compound key based upon the ICSE/GSM concept that a unique note can be chosen by a combination ICSE Key fields which will be expressed as a single hyphen delimited string in the service and when exposed to GSM. However, when used to interface with ICSE services it will be expressed in its individual key components.
models.readme:
Service Usage

This service is used to retrieve details of a specific Note returned from the current data model in ICSE which indicates that notes are stored as events and as additional info items in ICSE. The notes subset to be retrieved have been agreed on by GSM and ICSE as appropriate for this service. This service may be consumed at any time. The only requirements are that the note id is passed to this service. The note Id is a compound key based upon the ICSE/GSM concept that a unique note can be chosen by a combination ICSE Key fields which will be expressed as a single hyphen delimited string in the service and when exposed to GSM. However, when used to interface with ICSE services it will be expressed in its individual key components.

Service Behaviour

This service provides the following behaviour:
A consumer of this service provides:
Note Id
A consumer of this service receives:
Note Details which consist of
Note Text

The following notes types are returned in this service.
Event Notes
Assessment Notes
Permission Request Additional Info Notes
Any Audit information that is associated with the Activity and its associated activity notes.

Service Variants

None

Service Dependencies

None

Service Composition

This is not a composite service.

Service Flow

A normal flow for this service is to have the SV199 Retrieve Note Details Request called by the portal. SV199- Retrieve Note Details then calls the ICSE corresponding Retrieve Note Service. ICSE will then execute the Retrieve Note Details request and return a response message back to SV 199. This in turn is returned to the consumer.
SV199 has a Note Id key that is a compound key.
The key definition is located in the SV199 micro document.
The detail of this flow is as follows:
Service consumer invokes service SV199 on ESB using RetrieveNoteDetailsRequest.
Service SV199 then breaks up the noteId into the previously mentioned ICSE keys and creates an ICSE Request message.
Service SV199 invokes ICSE sending a request message.
ICSE receives the request and processes the Retrieve Note Details Request.
ICSE then sends a message back to service SV199.
Service SV199 sends a response message to the consumer.
Alternate Flow 1
The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when SV199 returns an error.
Service consumer invokes service SV199 on ESB using RetrieveNoteDetailsRequest.
Service SV199 then breaks up the noteId into the previously mentioned ICSE keys and creates an ICSE Request message.
Service SV199 invokes ICSE sending a request message.
ICSE receives the request and encounters an error.
ICSE then sends an error message back to service SV199.
SV199 detects the error and transforms ICSE Error into Enterprise Error
SV199 passes a response with this Enterprise Error to the consumer.

Service State Management Decisions

No state management required.

Service Variants

Service Composition

Service Flow

models.readme:
Service Usage

This service is used to retrieve notes related to a visa application. This includes only, notes on events and assessments.

Service Behaviour

The service retrieves all events and assessment notes related to a visa application. A consumer of this service sends a request message which contains Visa Application Id, unique identifier of a visa application.
If the service fails and an error message will be returned detailing the reason(s) why the notes related to the visa application could not be retrieved.
On the other hand, if the service succeeds, it will retrieve all the event and assessment notes related to the application identified by the unique identifier, visa application id supplied.

Service Variants

None

Service Dependencies

This service relies on the consumer providing a unique identifier of a Visa Application.

Service Composition

This is not a composite service.

Service Flow

A normal flow for this service is to have the SV280 Retrieve Application Notes request called by the portal. SV280 Retrieve Application Notes will then send the request to ICSE. ICSE will then execute the Retrieve Application Notes request and return a response message back to SV 280. This in turn is returned to the consumer.
The detail of this flow is as follows:
Service consumer invokes service SV280 on ESB using RetrieveApplicationNotesRequest.
SV280 creates ICSE request message, RetrieveConsolidatedNotesRequest.
Service SV280 invokes ICSE sending the request message.
ICSE receives the request and processes the Retrieve Application Notes Request.
ICSE then sends message, RetrieveConsolidatedNotesResponse back to service SV280.
Service SV280 sends a response message to the consumer.
Alternate Flow 1 (AF1)
The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when ICSE returns an error.
Service consumer invokes service SV280 on ESB using RetrieveApplicationNotesRequest.
SV280 creates ICSE request message, RetrieveConsolidatedNotesRequest.
Service SV280 invokes ICSE sending the request message.
ICSE receives the request and encounters an error.
ICSE then sends an error message back to service SV280.
SV280 detects the error and transforms ICSE Error into Enterprise Error
SV280 passes a response with this Enterprise Error to the consumer.
Alternate Flow 2 (AF2)
The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path when service timeout takes place.
Refer to document Service Timeouts.xls.

Service State Management Decisions

No state management required.

models.description:
Service Usage

The service is generic in nature and therefore support various different uses.
models.readme:
Service Usage

The service is generic in nature and therefore support various different uses.
GVP SfP10
The main purpose for GVP to use this service is to create a skeleton record of a Visa application in ICSE.
This service will expose the ICSE API directly in order to give GVP most flexibility.

Service Behaviour

The ESB exposes the genuine ICSE structure wrapped in a generic envelope. The ESB will use its framework for handling of the security tokens but it will not perform any data validation, data mapping or transformation of ICSE codes.
This service can be used to any kind of permission request.
The ESB will extract any error messages it receives from the provider (ICSE) and relay them using the normal exception handling procedure.

Service Variants

None

Service Dependencies

This service does not perform any enforcing actions like schema validation, but only passes the request message to ICSE.

Service Composition

This service is not a composite service i.e. it is not composed of other services within the Service Portfolio.

Service Flow

An event is generated by the Service Consumer which invokes the Maintain Permission Request service on the ESB
The ESB receives the request message which contains as actual payload a request message in genuine ICSE data format. The ESB unwraps the request message (transformation from MaintainPermissionRequestRequest into BusinessTransactionRequest) and passes it through to ICSE.
ICSE receives the request message and performs the requested operations.
ESB receives a response
Use AF1/AF2, if invocation failed.
ESB wraps the response (transformation from BusinessTransactionResponse into MaintainPermissionRequestResponse) and sends it to the service consumer
Alternate Flow 1 (AF1)
ESB transforms errors into enterprise error message and returns to the consumer. Please see the section Service Enterprise Return Code Message for more details.
Alternate Flow 2 (AF2)
If the service call was timeout, ESB should return SV330.MSG-to the consumer.

Service State Management Decisions

No state management required.

models.description:
Service Usage

The service is generic in nature and therefore support various different uses.
models.readme:
Service Usage

The service is generic in nature and therefore support various different uses.
GVP SfP10
As per Mini Macro SfP10 /1/ GVP will implement the functionality to cancel visas but will not support the associated review process. In case a review needs to be conducted the VPO still has to use ICSE.
This concept makes it necessary that GVP has the possibility to retrieve cancellation events from ICSE. This functionality will be implemented by this new transitional service. To give the consumer the most flexibility this service will expose the ICSE API directly.
In SfP10 this service will enable GVP to retrieve Cancellation Permission Requests including the following Cancellation Events:
Cancellation Commenced
Cancellation - Not Revoked
Cancellation - Revocation of Cancellation
Cancellation - Visa Not Cancelled
Cancelled
This functionality will be provided by ESB using a generic ICSE API.

Service Behaviour

The ESB exposes the genuine ICSE structure wrapped in a generic envelope. The ESB will use its framework for handling of the security tokens but it will not perform any data validation, data mapping or transformation of ICSE codes.
his service can be used to retrieve any kind of permission request.
The ESB will extract any error messages it receives from the provider (ICSE) and relay them using the normal exception handling procedure.

Service Variants

None

Service Dependencies

This service does not perform any enforcing actions like schema validation, but only passes the request message to ICSE and passes response messages from ICSE to the consumer.

Service Composition

This service is not a composite service, i.e. it is not composed of other services within the Service Portfolio.

Service Flow

An event is generated by the Service Consumer which invokes the Retrieve Permission Request service on the ESB
The ESB receives the request message which contains as actual payload a request message in genuine ICSE data format. The ESB unwraps the request message (transformation from RetrievePermissionRequestRequest into RetrieveApplicationRequest) and passes it through to ICSE.
ICSE receives the request message and performs the requested operations.
ESB receives a response
Use AF1/AF2, if invocation failed.
ESB wraps the response (transformation from RetrieveApplicationResponse into RetrievePermissionRequestResponse) and sends it to the service consumer
Alternate Flow 1 (AF1)
ESB transforms errors into enterprise error message and returns to the consumer. Please see the section Service Enterprise Return Code Message for more details.
Alternate Flow 2 (AF2)
If the service call was timeout, ESB should return SV331.MSG-E0 to the consumer.

Service State Management Decisions

models.description:
Service Usage

The Retrieve Visa service is to be used to retrieve specific information pertaining to a Visa Grant Number.
models.readme:
Service Usage

The Retrieve Visa service is to be used to retrieve specific information pertaining to a Visa Grant Number.

Service Behaviour

The Retrieves Visa details provided in this service include attributes within the business object:
Visa
Travel Document
Associated Evidence
Associated Name
The service uses TRIPS as the primary source of Visa Grants but is supplemented by ICSE for the VisaConditionCodes.
This service is designed to be called for each Visa where details regarding that Visa are required. This is usually (but not limited to) the current Visas for a person.

Service Variants

None

Service Dependencies

None

Service Composition

This service is not a composite service, i.e. it is not composed of other services within the Service Portfolio.

Service Flow

An event is generated by the Service Consumer which invokes the Retrieve Visa service on the ESB;
ESB transforms the eXML to Flat File taking only the Visa Grant Number from the eXML payload.
TRIPS Retrieve Visa API is invoked passing in the Visa Grant Number.
TRIPS Retrieve Visa API replies with a Flat File.
ESB transforms the Flat File to eXML and supplements the eXML with Descriptions from the TRIPS codes supplied. These will be both lookups and a hardcoded set of values.
ESB Replies to the consumer with the eXML message RetrieveVisaResponse.xml.
Alternate Flow 1 (AF1) RetrieveVisaSystemOfRecordFlag false.
Where TRIPS is the system of record for the complete set of Visa Conditions, the Visa conditions will be retrieved from TRIPS. In the cases that TRIPS does not hold the complete set of Visa Conditions, ICSE will be invoked to retrieve mandatory condition codes.
The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the Visa Grant Numkber retrieves a Visa that is an ICSE supplemented Visa.
An event is generated by the Service Consumer which invokes the Retrieve Visa service on the ESB;
ESB transforms the eXML to Flat File taking only the Visa Grant Number from the eXML payload.
TRIPS Retrieve Visa API is invoked passing in the Visa Grant Number.
TRIPS Retrieve Visa API replies with a Flat File.
ESB transforms the Flat File to eXML and supplements the eXML with Descriptions from the TRIPS codes supplied. These will be both lookups and a hardcoded set of values.
ESB inspects each Visa Grant Number from the TRIPS Response message
If the RetrieveVisaSystemOfRecordFlag indicates false, the system shall invoke ICSE as per item 7 & 8 below.
ESB creates an ICSE request message RetrieveMandConditionsRequest.xml using Visa Grant Number, VisaCriteriaSatisfiedCode, LodgementLocationType, VisaStatisticalCode, GrantDate, VisaClassCode, VisaSubClassCode, and User ID as inputs.
ICSE Response message RetrieveMandConditionsResponse.xml is passed back to the ESB. The Response message will include the VisaGrantNumber and MandatoryConditionCode.
RetrieveMandConditionsResponse.xml will not include any VisaGrantNumber when a MandatoryConditionCode does not exist.
In the event that the data provided to ICSE within the RetrieveMandConditionsRequest.xml (Visa Grant Number, VisaCriteriaSatisfiedCode, LodgementLocationType, VisaStatisticalCode, GrantDate, VisaClassCode, VisaSubClassCode, and User ID) does not match the information stored in ICSE, ICSE will produce an error in the RetrieveMandConditionsResponse.xml advising the VisaGrantNumber and the applicable error. Note: This will result in a warning from ESB, however the service will not fail.
ESB matches the MandatoryConditionCode with the VisaGrantNumber and supplements the TRIPS response with these codes merging all data.
ESB Replies to the consumer with the eXML message RetrieveVisaResponse.xml.
Alternate Flow 3 (AF3)
The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the TRIPS request fails.
An event is generated by the Service Consumer which invokes the Retrieve Visa service on the ESB;
ESB transforms the eXML to Flat File taking only the Visa Grant Number from the eXML payload.
TRIPS Retrieve Visa API is invoked passing in the Visa Grant Number.
TRIPS Retrieve Visa API replies with a Flat File as an error code.
ESB inspects the error, maps if able and returns an ESB SOAP Fault to the consumer with the error code and description.
Alternate Flow 4 (AF4)
The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the ICSE request fails.
An event is generated by the Service Consumer which invokes the Retrieve Visa service on the ESB;
ESB transforms the eXML to Flat File taking only the Visa Grant Number from the eXML payload.
TRIPS Retrieve Visa API is invoked passing in the Visa Grant Number.
TRIPS Retrieve Visa API replies with a Flat File.
ESB transforms the Flat File to eXML and supplements the eXML with Descriptions from the TRIPS codes supplied. These will be both lookups and a hardcoded set of values.
ESB inspects the Visa Grant Number from the TRIPS Response message
If the RetrieveVisaSystemOfRecordFlag indicates false, the system shall invoke ICSE as per item 7 & 8 below.
The ESB will include the following visa details (Visa Grant Number, VisaCriteriaSatisfiedCode, LodgementLocationType, VisaStatisticalCode, GrantDate and User ID), within the one RetrieveMandConditionsRequest.xml.
ICSE Response message RetrieveMandConditionsResponse.xml is passed back to the ESB. The Response message will include the VisaGrantNumber and MandatoryConditionCode.

  1. RetrieveMandConditionsResponse.xml will not include any VisaGrantNumber when a MandatoryConditionCode does not exist.
  2. In the event that there is a security error, the ICSE Response message RetrieveMandConditionsResponse.xml is passed back to the ESB displaying the appropriate code e.g. 10021, 10002, 10004
  3. In the event that the data provided to ICSE within the RetrieveMandConditionsRequest.xml (Visa Grant Number, VisaCriteriaSatisfiedCode, LodgementLocationType, VisaStatisticalCode, GrantDate and User ID) does not match the information stored in ICSE, ICSE will produce an error in the RetrieveMandConditionsResponse.xml advising the VisaGrantNumber and the applicable error. Note: This will result in a warning from ESB, however the service will not fail.
  4. ESB inspects the error, maps if able and returns an ESB SOAP Fault to the consumer with the error code and description.

Service Usage

This service is used to retrieve the health integrity concern details to the consumer. It includes all details including history. Only one single client is handled per service call.
Consumer provides the Applicant Id (ICSE Client ID) in the request to retrieve health integrity concern details from the ICSE application.

Service Behaviour

The consumer of this service invokes this service with Applicant Id (ICSE Client ID). This service retrieves health integrity concern details from ICSE and returns to Consumer. Any exception raised will be returned to consumer as a soap-fault message.

Service Variants

None

Service Dependencies

None

Service Composition

This service is a composite service.

Service Flow

An event is generated by the Service Consumer which invokes the Retrieve ICSE Health Integrity of Concern service on the ESB;
ESB transforms RetrieveICSEHealthIntegrityOfConcerntRequest to RetrieveHealthConcernRequest message and sends to ICSE.
When RetrieveICSEHealthIntegrityOfConcernRequest message has ApplicantId as PARTY_ID, ESB call SV288 Retrieve Consolidated Party Identifiers Service to transform PartyId to ClientId.
ESB uses ClientId to call ICSE application.
ICSE returns RetrieveHealthConcernResponse to ESB.
ESB examines the RetrieveHealthConcernResponse Messages within to determine whether there is any error returned by ICSE, if so, use AF1.
Use AF2 if SV288 returns error.
ESB transforms back from RetrieveHealthConcernResponse message to RetrieveICSEHealthIntegrityOfConcernResponse message.
Use AF3 if ICSE request is timeout.
ESB returns health integrity concern details or error message(in case of exception raise) to Service Consumer
Alternate Flow 1 (AF1)
The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the primary provider raises an error.
ESB transforms ICSE Error into Enterprise Error Message.
ESB returns response with Enterprise Error payload.
Alternate Flow 2 (AF2)
The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the service SV288 raises an error.
ESB detects that SV288 has returned an error
ESB transforms SV288 error into Enterprise Error Message.
ESB returns response with Enterprise Error to Consumer
Alternate Flow 3 (AF3)
If the service call was timeout, ESB should return SV395.MSG-E00 to the consumer.

Transformation

models.description:
Service Usage

This service is used to update the health integrity details of the consumer in ICSE application and returns an acknowledgment.
models.readme:
Service Usage

This service is used to update the health integrity details of the consumer in ICSE application and returns an acknowledgment.

Service Behaviour

The consumer of this service invokes this service with the health integrity details along with the ApplicantId in the request to update the health Integrity details in ICSE. When successfully updated by ICSE an acknowledgment is return to consumer. Any exceptions raised were returned to the consumer as soap-fault with exception details.

Service Variants

None

Service Dependencies

None

Service Composition

This service is a composite service.

Service Flow

An event is generated by the Service Consumer which invokes the Close ICSE Health Integrity Of Concern service on the ESB;
ESB transforms CloseICSEHealthIntegrityOfConcernRequest to Request message and sends to ICSE.
When CloseICSEHealthIntegrityOfConcernRequest message has ApplicationId as PARTY_ID, ESB call SV288 Modify Consolidated Party Identifiers Service to transform PartyId to ClientId.
ESB uses ClientId to call ICSE application.
ICSE returns Response to ESB.
ESB examines the Response Messages within to determine whether there is any error returned by ICSE, if so, use AF1.
Use AF2 if SV288 returns error.
ESB transforms back from Response message to CloseICSEHealthIntegrityOfConcernResponse message.
Use AF3 if ICSE request is timeout.
ESB returns health integrity concern details or error message(in case of exception raise) to Service Consumer
Alternate Flow 1 (AF1)
The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the primary provider raises an error.
ESB transforms ICSE Error into Enterprise Error Message.
ESB returns response with Enterprise Error payload.
Alternate Flow 2 (AF2)
The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the service SV288 raises an error.
ESB detects that SV288 has returned an error
ESB transforms SV288 error into Enterprise Error Message.
ESB returns response with Enterprise Error to Consumer
Alternate Flow 3 (AF3)
If the service call was timeout, ESB should return SV396.MSG-E00 to the consumer.

Transformation

Transformations
DIMA_DCD d15 Service Specification - SV396 - v01.0 Close ICSE Health Integrity of Concern.xls

Service State Management Decisions

No state management required.

models.readme:
Service Usage

This service is consumed by skill select at the beginning of the eVisa lodgement process and provided by eLodgement. The external interface for this service is a WDSL named XS021 but is nothing additional other than the WSDL compliancy. For this documentation, SV461 service behaviour and XS021 behaviour can be considered one in the same.

Service Behaviour

This service provides eLodgement with the basics of the Visa Application and Applicant. The response from eLodgement provides for each Client the ApplicationClientId, Transaction ID List, Serial Number and the Role Code.

Service Variants

XS021 is a direct derivative of this service.

Service Dependencies

Service Composition

An event is generated by the Service Consumer which invokes the CacheProspectiveVisaApplicantDetails service.
Skill Select sends a compliant XS021 message to datapower.
Datapower forwards this content as a compliant SV461 message where no transform is required on the content of the message.

Service Flow

Alternate Flow 1 (AF1)
The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the primary provider raises an error.
eLodgement transforms ENTR0001 into Enterprise Error Message as unknown. No error messages have been provided as part of the requirements so all errors are returned as Unknown.
Datapower returns response with Enterprise Error payload.

Transformation

No transformations exist for this service.

Service State Management Decisions

No state management required.

This service provides an interface for maintaining Visa Cancellation Events. Consumers of this service will stop using SV330 Maintain Permission Request for maintaining Visa Cancellations.
This service interface will be used to create and maintain visa cancellation events in ICSE.

Service Behaviour

This service will create or modify an existing cancellation permission request in ICSE.

Service Variants

None

Service Dependencies

None

Service Composition

This is not a composite service.

Service Flow

An event is generated by the Service Consumer which invokes the MaintainVisaCancellationEvents service on the ESB by sending Maintain Visa Cancellation request message.
ESB validates and transforms Maintain Visa Cancellation request message into Business Transaction Request, and sends the message to ICSE.
ICSE validates and processes the request, and sends the Business Transaction Response message back to ESB.
ESB validates and transforms the Business Transaction Response message to Maintain Visa Cancellation Response, and sends the message back to the Service Consumer.
Exception Flow 1
If any of the exception scenarios listed in Section 4 Return Codes and Messages an exception message is send back to the consumer.

No state management required.

models.description:
Service Usage

The service verifies if the details of a immi card provided are associated with a valid visa that the department holds in it's records.
models.readme:
Service Usage

The service verifies if the details of a immi card provided are associated with a valid visa that the department holds in it's records.

Service Behaviour

The consumer sends a request with details of the Australian Immi Card to be verified. The provider will send a response status (yes/no/error) which confirms if the details provided match a document held in our records. This service accepts inbound requests from external agencies (ie. it is the provider for the DVS service). In the case of an external request from DVS, the VerificationRequestIdentifier, VerificationRequestDateTime, VerificationRequestorAgency and VerificationRequestDocumentType elements are mandatory. For all outbound calls, the WSGW will generate the DVS mandated elements VerificationRequestNumber, VersionNumber, VerificationRequestDateTime and VerificationRequestorAgency during the transform into the DVS provider message.

Service Flow

  1. Consumer sends an enterprise SV629 request message to the ESB.
  2. ESB transforms the enterprise message into an internal DVS message.
  3. ESB sends the internal DVS message to the WSGW.
  4. WSGW transforms the internal DVS message into an external DVS message.
  5. WSGW sends the external DVS message to Oakton/DVS.
  6. Oakton respond to the ESB via WSGW with a generic Verification Response message.
  7. The generic response message is transformed into a SV629 response.

Transformation

Transformation exists on the ESB between enterprise and legacy internal DVS messages. The internal DVS messages are transformed into the external DVS messages on the WSGW.

models.description:

models.readme:
Service Usage

This service is used to validate information which is being submitted as part of a notification of sponsorship change.

Service Behaviour

The service will validate the following: 1. The business service identifier provided exists and is related to a sponsorship application. 2. If nomination information is provided - that the business service identifier provided exists, is related to a nomination application, and that nomination application is associated with the sponsorship provided. 3. The nominees date of birth provided matches that of the primary applicant record on the nomination.

Transformation

Transformation exists on the ESB to transform enterprise messages into and from MaintainSponsorshipDetails provider messages for ICSE.

models.description:
Service Usage

An approved Standard Business Sponsor (SBS) is required to meet certain sponsorship obligations. This service is used to notify subscribers of changes to their details in the context of a sponsorship application. Details which can be updated by the sponsor can include contact information, management roles, trading name, annual turnover figures, evidence checklists and the associated application contact.
models.readme:
Service Usage

An approved Standard Business Sponsor (SBS) is required to meet certain sponsorship obligations. This service is used to notify subscribers of changes to their details in the context of a sponsorship application. Details which can be updated by the sponsor can include contact information, management roles, trading name, annual turnover figures, evidence checklists and the associated application contact.

Service Behaviour

This is an asynchronous service. The response payload will contain a success flag and the associated TRN/PRN of the application which has been updated. If there are any errors returned from the subscriber, a SOAP fault will be returned to the publisher.

Transformation

Enterprise messages routed to ICSE are transformed on the ESB into an ICSE provider BusinessTransactionRequest.xsd message

Service Usage

When Business data in ICSE changes, ICSE sends updates to the application cached in WM. (the application data would have been previously cached in WM via SV102).
models.readme:
Service Usage

When Business data in ICSE changes, ICSE sends updates to the application cached in WM. (the application data would have been previously cached in WM via SV102).

WM is responsible retrying the updates if there are any issues

models.description:
Service Usage

This service notifies work management of Work items along with associations to other business dealings and roles. Within these associtaions two levels of filters can be applied that are used by WMAN and consumers to search and filter data as groups of work items. This allows flexability to create as many filters as business areas require but only used on the cotext of filters. The Work Item can be referenced by the Business Service ID or the Work Item Id for updates.
